if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
window.MM['ent_p2_larynx']=[
  {q:"A 55-year-old smoker presents with progressive hoarseness for 4 months. Flexible laryngoscopy shows a lesion confined to one true vocal cord with preserved mobility. Which anatomical feature explains why hoarseness occurs early in glottic lesions?",o:["Rich lymphatic drainage of vocal cords","Direct involvement of recurrent laryngeal nerve","Vibratory role of true vocal cords in phonation","Close relation to thyroid gland","Abundant mucus glands in cords"],a:2,e:"True vocal cords are essential for sound production because their mucosal vibration generates phonation. Hoarseness develops clinically early even with small glottic lesions.<br><br>This early symptom contributes to relatively favorable prognosis of glottic cancers compared with supraglottic tumors.<br><br>Rich lymphatics (option A), recurrent laryngeal involvement (option B), thyroid relation (option D), and mucus glands (option E) are less responsible.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Bilateral abductor vocal cord paralysis most commonly produces:",o:["Severe aspiration only","Aphonia without stridor","Inspiratory stridor with relatively preserved voice","Hypernasal speech","Complete loss of cough reflex"],a:2,e:"In bilateral abductor paralysis, cords remain near midline causing airway narrowing. Inspiratory stridor develops clinically while phonation may remain relatively preserved.<br><br>The recurrent laryngeal nerves supply posterior cricoarytenoid muscles, the sole abductors of vocal cords.<br><br>Aspiration alone (option A), aphonia (option B), hypernasality (option D), and absent cough reflex (option E) are less characteristic.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The only abductor muscle of the vocal cords is the:",o:["Lateral cricoarytenoid","Cricothyroid","Posterior cricoarytenoid","Thyroarytenoid","Interarytenoid"],a:2,e:"Posterior cricoarytenoid muscles abduct vocal cords during inspiration and maintain airway patency. Bilateral paralysis develops clinically with stridor and respiratory distress.<br><br>Damage to recurrent laryngeal nerves commonly affects this critical function.<br><br>Lateral cricoarytenoid (option A), cricothyroid (option B), thyroarytenoid (option D), and interarytenoid (option E) are adductors or tensors.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"During thyroid surgery, injury to recurrent laryngeal nerve most commonly causes:",o:["Vocal cord paralysis","Hypernasal speech","Tongue deviation","Facial asymmetry","Dysphagia only"],a:0,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve supplies all intrinsic laryngeal muscles except cricothyroid. Hoarseness develops clinically after unilateral nerve injury.<br><br>Bilateral injury may produce life-threatening airway obstruction.<br><br>Hypernasality (option B), tongue deviation (option C), facial asymmetry (option D), and isolated dysphagia (option E) are less characteristic.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Sensory supply above the vocal cords is provided mainly by the:",o:["Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Internal laryngeal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve only","Facial nerve"],a:2,e:"The internal laryngeal nerve supplies sensation above the vocal cords including supraglottis. Loss of protective cough reflex develops clinically after injury.<br><br>It is a branch of superior laryngeal nerve entering through thyrohyoid membrane.<br><br>Recurrent laryngeal nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option B), glossopharyngeal nerve only (option D), and facial nerve (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"Cricothyroid muscle is supplied by the:",o:["External laryngeal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Internal laryngeal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:0,e:"The cricothyroid muscle tenses vocal cords and is innervated by external laryngeal nerve. Voice fatigue and inability to produce high-pitched sounds develop clinically after injury.<br><br>This nerve is vulnerable during superior thyroid vessel ligation.<br><br>Recurrent laryngeal nerve (option B), internal laryngeal nerve (option C), glossopharyngeal nerve (option D), and hypoglossal nerve (option E) are incorrect supplies.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops aspiration after supraglottic laryngectomy because supraglottis normally functions primarily in:",o:["Voice resonance only","Air conditioning only","Airway protection during swallowing","Olfaction","Endocrine secretion"],a:2,e:"The supraglottic larynx protects lower airway during deglutition through epiglottic and sphincteric action. Aspiration develops clinically when these mechanisms are impaired.<br><br>Swallow rehabilitation is therefore essential after supraglottic surgery.<br><br>Voice resonance (option A), air conditioning (option B), olfaction (option D), and endocrine secretion (option E) are less important functions.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The narrowest part of adult larynx is the:",o:["Laryngeal inlet","Vestibule","Rima glottidis","Subglottis","Pyriform fossa"],a:2,e:"The rima glottidis is the narrowest functional airway segment in adults. Stridor develops clinically when glottic obstruction occurs.<br><br>Its caliber changes dynamically with respiration and phonation.<br><br>Laryngeal inlet (option A), vestibule (option B), subglottis (option D), and pyriform fossa (option E) are wider structures.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with acute subglottic edema develops severe stridor because the narrowest part of pediatric airway is the:",o:["Supraglottis","Glottis","Subglottis at cricoid level","Pyriform fossa","Nasopharynx"],a:2,e:"The pediatric airway is narrowest at subglottic cricoid region. Small amounts of edema produce clinically significant airway compromise and stridor.<br><br>This anatomical feature explains severity of croup in children.<br><br>Supraglottis (option A), glottis (option B), pyriform fossa (option D), and nasopharynx (option E) are less narrow.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy typically presents with:",o:["Aphonia and severe stridor","Hoarseness and weak cough","Complete inability to swallow","Facial asymmetry","Tongue paralysis"],a:1,e:"Unilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis leaves one cord immobile causing incomplete glottic closure. Hoarseness and ineffective cough develop clinically.<br><br>Compensation by opposite cord may improve symptoms over time.<br><br>Aphonia with severe stridor (option A), inability to swallow (option C), facial asymmetry (option D), and tongue paralysis (option E) are less characteristic.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"During tracheostomy, the thyroid isthmus usually lies anterior to:",o:["Second and third tracheal rings","First tracheal ring","Cricoid cartilage only","Arytenoid cartilage","Epiglottis"],a:0,e:"The thyroid isthmus commonly crosses second and third tracheal rings and may require retraction or division during tracheostomy. Hemorrhage develops clinically if improperly handled.<br><br>Knowledge of this relation is essential for safe airway surgery.<br><br>First tracheal ring (option B), cricoid cartilage (option C), arytenoid cartilage (option D), and epiglottis (option E) are incorrect relations.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The lymphatic drainage of true vocal cords is clinically important because it is:",o:["Nearly absent","Extremely rich bilaterally","Connected directly to thoracic duct","Draining only to submental nodes","Independent of cervical nodes"],a:0,e:"True vocal cords possess sparse lymphatic drainage. Early lymph node metastasis develops clinically less commonly in glottic carcinoma.<br><br>This contributes to favorable prognosis of early-stage glottic cancer.<br><br>Rich bilateral drainage (option B), direct thoracic drainage (option C), submental drainage (option D), and absence of cervical relation (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal trauma develops surgical emphysema of neck because air escapes from:",o:["Disrupted laryngotracheal airway","Thyroid gland","Esophagus only","Carotid sheath","Thoracic duct"],a:0,e:"Laryngeal fractures may disrupt airway mucosa allowing air leakage into cervical soft tissues. Crepitus develops clinically on palpation of neck.<br><br>Airway stabilization is the priority in major laryngeal trauma.<br><br>Thyroid gland (option B), esophagus alone (option C), carotid sheath (option D), and thoracic duct (option E) are less likely sources.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The anterior commissure of larynx is clinically important because tumors here:",o:["Never spread to cartilage","May spread early to thyroid cartilage","Produce severe aspiration immediately","Always metastasize distantly first","Cause facial pain early"],a:1,e:"The anterior commissure is closely related to thyroid cartilage through Broyles ligament. Early cartilage invasion develops clinically in glottic cancers involving this region.<br><br>This influences staging and surgical planning significantly.<br><br>Absence of cartilage spread (option A), immediate aspiration (option C), distant metastasis first (option D), and facial pain (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"During indirect laryngoscopy, the first structure usually visualized is the:",o:["Epiglottis","Arytenoid cartilage","Vocal process","Subglottis","Trachea"],a:0,e:"The epiglottis forms the anterior boundary of laryngeal inlet and is commonly visualized first during examination. Dysphagia develops clinically when epiglottic pathology occurs.<br><br>Indirect laryngoscopy remains an important office-based assessment tool.<br><br>Arytenoid cartilage (option B), vocal process (option C), subglottis (option D), and trachea (option E) are visualized deeper.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops inability to produce high-pitched sounds after thyroidectomy. The most likely injured nerve is:",o:["Recurrent laryngeal nerve","External laryngeal nerve","Internal laryngeal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:1,e:"External laryngeal nerve supplies cricothyroid muscle responsible for vocal cord tension. Voice fatigue and reduced pitch develop clinically after injury.<br><br>The nerve is vulnerable during ligation of superior thyroid vessels.<br><br>Recurrent laryngeal nerve (option A), internal laryngeal nerve (option C), glossopharyngeal nerve (option D), and hypoglossal nerve (option E) produce different deficits.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis is most likely to require:",o:["Tympanoplasty","Emergency airway intervention","Mastoidectomy","Tonsillectomy","Septoplasty"],a:1,e:"Bilateral recurrent laryngeal paralysis fixes cords near midline causing critical airway narrowing. Inspiratory stridor and respiratory distress develop clinically.<br><br>Tracheostomy may become lifesaving in severe bilateral paralysis.<br><br>Tympanoplasty (option A), mastoidectomy (option C), tonsillectomy (option D), and septoplasty (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The cough reflex from supraglottic mucosa is mediated primarily through the:",o:["Internal laryngeal nerve","Facial nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve only","Hypoglossal nerve","Sympathetic chain"],a:0,e:"The internal laryngeal nerve provides sensory innervation above vocal cords and initiates protective cough reflex. Silent aspiration develops clinically after sensory loss.<br><br>It enters larynx through thyrohyoid membrane.<br><br>Facial nerve (option B), recurrent laryngeal nerve alone (option C), hypoglossal nerve (option D), and sympathetic chain (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with supraglottic carcinoma commonly presents late because supraglottic lesions:",o:["Do not affect phonation early","Lack lymphatic drainage","Are painless and avascular","Never ulcerate","Spare swallowing mechanism completely"],a:0,e:"Supraglottic lesions may grow significantly before affecting true vocal cord vibration. Dysphagia and neck nodes develop clinically before hoarseness appears.<br><br>Rich lymphatic drainage also contributes to earlier nodal metastasis.<br><br>Lack of lymphatics (option B), avascularity (option C), absent ulceration (option D), and complete swallowing preservation (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve enters larynx posterior to the:",o:["Cricothyroid membrane","Thyroid cartilage lamina","Cricoarytenoid joint","Superior thyroid artery","Hyoid bone"],a:2,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve enters larynx near cricoarytenoid joint beneath inferior constrictor muscle. Hoarseness develops clinically after injury during neck surgery.<br><br>This relation is important during thyroidectomy and laryngeal procedures.<br><br>Cricothyroid membrane (option A), thyroid lamina (option B), superior thyroid artery (option D), and hyoid bone (option E) are less accurate relations.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal edema develops inspiratory stridor because obstruction is occurring at the:",o:["Extrathoracic upper airway","Main bronchi","Alveolar level","Pleural cavity","Lower esophagus"],a:0,e:"Inspiratory stridor results from turbulent airflow through narrowed extrathoracic airway. Laryngeal edema produces clinically high-pitched inspiratory sounds.<br><br>This is an important sign of upper airway compromise.<br><br>Main bronchi (option B), alveoli (option C), pleural cavity (option D), and esophagus (option E) do not produce stridor.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent laryngeal nerve injury after esophagectomy has immobile vocal cord lying in:",o:["Cadaveric or paramedian position","Fully abducted position","Extreme adduction","Vertical orientation","Lateralized position only"],a:0,e:"Denervated vocal cords typically rest in paramedian or cadaveric position. Hoarseness and aspiration develop clinically depending on compensation.<br><br>The exact position depends on balance of remaining laryngeal muscle tone.<br><br>Full abduction (option B), extreme adduction (option C), vertical orientation (option D), and complete lateralization (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"During emergency cricothyrotomy, the incision is made through the:",o:["Thyrohyoid membrane","Tracheal rings","Cricothyroid membrane","Pretracheal fascia only","Thyroid cartilage lamina"],a:2,e:"Cricothyrotomy rapidly establishes airway through cricothyroid membrane between thyroid and cricoid cartilages. Severe airway obstruction develops clinically in emergencies requiring this procedure.<br><br>It is faster than formal tracheostomy in acute situations.<br><br>Thyrohyoid membrane (option A), tracheal rings (option B), pretracheal fascia (option D), and thyroid lamina (option E) are incorrect sites.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with aspiration during swallowing most likely has impaired function of:",o:["Vestibular folds only","Supraglottic protective mechanisms","Cricoid cartilage alone","Thyroid gland","Eustachian tube"],a:1,e:"The larynx prevents aspiration through epiglottic tilt, laryngeal elevation, and vocal cord closure. Coughing during swallowing develops clinically when these mechanisms fail.<br><br>Neurological disease commonly impairs these protective functions.<br><br>Vestibular folds alone (option A), cricoid cartilage (option C), thyroid gland (option D), and Eustachian tube (option E) are less responsible.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with glottic carcinoma has favorable prognosis mainly because:",o:["Tumors are painless","Vocal cords are richly vascular","Early hoarseness leads to early diagnosis","Subglottis blocks spread","Airway obstruction occurs immediately"],a:2,e:"Even small glottic lesions affect phonation because true vocal cords are essential for voice production. Persistent hoarseness develops clinically early in disease.<br><br>This permits diagnosis at earlier stages compared with supraglottic cancers.<br><br>Painlessness (option A), rich vascularity (option B), subglottic barrier (option D), and immediate obstruction (option E) are less important reasons.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The framework of larynx is maintained primarily by:",o:["Fibrous septa only","Cervical vertebrae","Cartilaginous skeleton","Strap muscles exclusively","Thyroid gland"],a:2,e:"The larynx is supported by cartilages including thyroid, cricoid, arytenoid, and epiglottic structures. Airway collapse develops clinically when framework integrity is disrupted.<br><br>This skeleton maintains airway patency and enables phonation.<br><br>Fibrous septa (option A), vertebrae (option B), strap muscles (option D), and thyroid gland (option E) are supportive but not primary framework.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient undergoing supraglottic laryngectomy is counseled regarding postoperative aspiration risk because the epiglottis primarily functions to:",o:["Produce mucus","Direct food away from airway","Maintain vocal pitch","Warm inspired air only","Support thyroid gland"],a:1,e:"The epiglottis contributes to airway protection by deflecting bolus away during swallowing. Aspiration develops clinically after supraglottic surgery until compensation occurs.<br><br>Swallow rehabilitation is therefore important postoperatively.<br><br>Mucus production (option A), vocal pitch (option C), air warming (option D), and thyroid support (option E) are secondary or unrelated roles.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal trauma develops hoarseness and palpable neck crepitus after road traffic accident. The most likely injury is:",o:["Nasal fracture only","Salivary fistula","Laryngeal cartilage fracture","Mastoid fracture","Thyroid cyst rupture"],a:2,e:"Blunt neck trauma may fracture thyroid or cricoid cartilage disrupting airway mucosa. Surgical emphysema develops clinically because air escapes into cervical tissues.<br><br>Urgent airway assessment is essential in suspected laryngeal trauma.<br><br>Nasal fracture (option A), salivary fistula (option B), mastoid fracture (option D), and thyroid cyst rupture (option E) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The richest lymphatic drainage within larynx is found in the:",o:["True vocal cords","Anterior commissure only","Supraglottis","Subglottis exclusively","Cricothyroid membrane"],a:2,e:"The supraglottis has abundant lymphatic drainage leading to early cervical nodal metastasis. Dysphagia and neck swelling develop clinically in supraglottic cancers.<br><br>This contrasts with sparse lymphatics of true vocal cords.<br><br>True cords (option A), anterior commissure (option B), subglottis alone (option D), and cricothyroid membrane (option E) are less richly supplied.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral vocal cord paralysis develops cyanosis during exertion. The physiological reason is inability of cords to:",o:["Adduct during speech","Produce mucus","Abduct adequately during inspiration","Protect lower airway during swallowing only","Vibrate during phonation"],a:2,e:"Posterior cricoarytenoid paralysis prevents widening of glottic airway during inspiration. Exertional dyspnea and stridor develop clinically because airflow becomes restricted.<br><br>Severe bilateral paralysis may require tracheostomy for airway maintenance.<br><br>Adduction during speech (option A), mucus production (option B), swallowing protection only (option D), and phonatory vibration (option E) are less responsible.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 24-year-old motorcyclist presents after blunt anterior neck trauma with hoarseness, painful swallowing, and palpable crepitus over the neck. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Laryngeal framework injury with surgical emphysema","Acute epiglottitis","Retropharyngeal abscess","Vocal cord nodule","Ludwig angina"],a:0,e:"Blunt laryngeal trauma may fracture thyroid or cricoid cartilages, allowing air leakage into cervical tissues. Hoarseness and subcutaneous emphysema develop clinically after airway disruption.<br><br>Early airway assessment is essential because edema may rapidly worsen obstruction.<br><br>Epiglottitis (option B), retropharyngeal abscess (option C), vocal nodules (option D), and Ludwig angina (option E) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The first priority in management of severe laryngeal trauma is:",o:["CT scan neck","Voice assessment","Airway stabilization","Flexible nasendoscopy","Antibiotic therapy"],a:2,e:"Airway compromise is the most dangerous immediate complication of laryngeal trauma. Stridor and respiratory distress develop clinically due to edema, hematoma, or cartilage disruption.<br><br>Definitive airway control should precede imaging or extensive examination.<br><br>CT scan (option A), voice assessment (option B), nasendoscopy (option D), and antibiotics (option E) are secondary considerations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal trauma develops inspiratory stridor and cyanosis. The physiological cause is:",o:["Vocal cord overabduction","Increased mucus secretion","Glottic airway narrowing","Pulmonary embolism","Diaphragmatic paralysis"],a:2,e:"Trauma-induced edema or displaced cartilage fragments narrow the glottic airway causing turbulent airflow. Inspiratory stridor develops clinically as airway obstruction worsens.<br><br>Rapid deterioration may occur because edema progresses after injury.<br><br>Overabduction (option A), mucus secretion (option B), pulmonary embolism (option D), and diaphragmatic paralysis (option E) are less relevant.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after strangulation injury complains of hoarseness and odynophagia. Flexible laryngoscopy reveals arytenoid swelling and vocal cord hematoma. The best initial management is:",o:["Immediate total laryngectomy","Observation with airway monitoring and steroids","Radical neck dissection","Emergency thyroidectomy","Radiotherapy"],a:1,e:"Minor laryngeal trauma without unstable fractures may be managed conservatively. Hoarseness and painful swallowing develop clinically due to mucosal edema and hematoma.<br><br>Close airway observation remains essential because delayed obstruction may occur.<br><br>Laryngectomy (option A), neck dissection (option C), thyroidectomy (option D), and radiotherapy (option E) are inappropriate.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe blunt neck trauma develops loss of normal thyroid cartilage prominence and palpable crepitus. The most likely injury is fracture of the:",o:["Hyoid bone only","Epiglottis","Thyroid cartilage","Aryepiglottic fold","Cricothyroid membrane alone"],a:2,e:"The thyroid cartilage forms the major palpable anterior laryngeal framework. Fracture produces deformity and surgical emphysema clinically after blunt trauma.<br><br>Associated mucosal tears may further compromise airway patency.<br><br>Hyoid injury (option A), epiglottic trauma (option B), aryepiglottic fold injury (option D), and isolated membrane injury (option E) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient involved in road traffic accident develops progressive neck swelling and respiratory distress several hours later. This delayed deterioration is mainly due to:",o:["Immediate vocal cord paralysis","Progressive edema and hematoma formation","Pulmonary fibrosis","Acute sinusitis","Salivary fistula formation"],a:1,e:"Laryngeal trauma may initially appear mild before progressive edema and hematoma worsen airway narrowing. Stridor develops clinically hours after injury in some patients.<br><br>Continuous observation is therefore crucial after neck trauma.<br><br>Immediate paralysis (option A), pulmonary fibrosis (option C), sinusitis (option D), and salivary fistula (option E) are less responsible.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation of choice for evaluating laryngeal cartilage fractures in stable patients is:",o:["Tympanometry","Pure tone audiometry","CT scan neck","Thyroid scan","Barium swallow only"],a:2,e:"CT scanning accurately identifies laryngeal fractures, airway narrowing, and soft tissue emphysema. Hoarseness and neck pain develop clinically after significant trauma.<br><br>Imaging guides decisions regarding conservative versus surgical management.<br><br>Tympanometry (option A), audiometry (option B), thyroid scan (option D), and barium swallow alone (option E) are less useful.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with penetrating laryngeal injury develops coughing immediately after swallowing liquids. This symptom suggests:",o:["Vocal nodules","Ménière disease","Laryngotracheal aspiration risk","Septal hematoma","Glossitis"],a:2,e:"Penetrating injuries may impair laryngeal protective mechanisms or create pharyngolaryngeal communication. Aspiration develops clinically with coughing during swallowing.<br><br>Swallowing assessment is important before oral feeding.<br><br>Vocal nodules (option A), Ménière disease (option B), septal hematoma (option D), and glossitis (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Emergency cricothyrotomy is performed through the:",o:["Thyrohyoid membrane","Cricoid cartilage","Cricothyroid membrane","Tracheal rings below isthmus","Aryepiglottic fold"],a:2,e:"The cricothyroid membrane provides rapid access to airway during emergencies. Severe upper airway obstruction develops clinically in major laryngeal trauma.<br><br>The membrane lies between thyroid and cricoid cartilages and is relatively avascular.<br><br>Thyrohyoid membrane (option A), cricoid cartilage (option B), tracheal rings (option D), and aryepiglottic fold (option E) are incorrect sites.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal trauma develops bilateral vocal cord immobility. The most dangerous complication is:",o:["Dysphonia only","Severe aspiration only","Acute airway obstruction","Hypernasal speech","Glossopharyngeal neuralgia"],a:2,e:"Bilateral vocal cord immobility narrows the glottic airway critically. Inspiratory stridor and cyanosis develop clinically due to inability of cords to abduct.<br><br>Emergency airway intervention may become necessary.<br><br>Dysphonia alone (option A), aspiration only (option B), hypernasality (option D), and neuralgia (option E) are less dangerous.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with blunt laryngeal trauma develops extensive subcutaneous emphysema extending into chest wall. The air most likely escaped from:",o:["Thyroid gland","Internal jugular vein","Torn laryngotracheal mucosa","Thoracic duct","Salivary duct"],a:2,e:"Mucosal disruption allows air leakage into fascial planes causing surgical emphysema. Crepitus develops clinically on palpation of neck and chest wall.<br><br>Associated airway injury must always be excluded.<br><br>Thyroid gland (option A), jugular vein (option B), thoracic duct (option D), and salivary duct (option E) are incorrect sources.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe laryngeal trauma undergoes tracheostomy. The preferred site is usually:",o:["Through cricoid cartilage","Directly through thyroid gland","Between second and third tracheal rings","Through thyrohyoid membrane","Through vocal cords"],a:2,e:"Standard tracheostomy is commonly performed between second and third tracheal rings below the laryngeal injury. Respiratory distress develops clinically in major airway trauma.<br><br>Avoiding damaged laryngeal structures reduces further injury.<br><br>Cricoid cartilage (option A), thyroid gland (option B), thyrohyoid membrane (option D), and vocal cords (option E) are inappropriate sites.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with isolated unilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve injury after neck trauma most commonly presents with:",o:["Hoarseness","Complete aphonia","Bilateral stridor","Facial asymmetry","Tongue deviation"],a:0,e:"Unilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve injury leaves one vocal cord immobile causing incomplete glottic closure. Hoarseness develops clinically with weak cough.<br><br>Airway compromise is usually less severe than bilateral paralysis.<br><br>Complete aphonia (option B), bilateral stridor (option C), facial asymmetry (option D), and tongue deviation (option E) are less typical.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with blunt neck trauma develops odynophagia and hemoptysis. Flexible laryngoscopy reveals mucosal tear over false cord. The best management is usually:",o:["Conservative airway observation and antibiotics","Immediate radical laryngectomy","Radiotherapy","Neck dissection","Thyroidectomy"],a:0,e:"Minor mucosal laryngeal injuries without unstable fractures may heal conservatively. Painful swallowing and mild hemoptysis develop clinically due to mucosal disruption.<br><br>Serial airway assessment remains important during recovery.<br><br>Laryngectomy (option B), radiotherapy (option C), neck dissection (option D), and thyroidectomy (option E) are unnecessary.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest cause of blunt laryngeal trauma is:",o:["Gunshot injury","Fish bone ingestion","Road traffic accidents","Chronic smoking","Acute epiglottitis"],a:2,e:"Blunt neck trauma during road traffic accidents commonly injures the laryngeal framework. Hoarseness and airway compromise develop clinically depending on severity.<br><br>Seatbelt and dashboard impacts are classical mechanisms.<br><br>Gunshot injury (option A), fish bone ingestion (option B), smoking (option D), and epiglottitis (option E) are less common causes.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal fracture develops persistent hoarseness months later due to:",o:["Vocal cord scarring and malalignment","Sinusitis","Otitis media","Facial paralysis","Glossopharyngeal injury only"],a:0,e:"Improper healing after laryngeal trauma may impair normal vocal cord vibration. Chronic dysphonia develops clinically because of fibrosis and framework distortion.<br><br>Early anatomical repair improves long-term voice outcomes.<br><br>Sinusitis (option B), otitis media (option C), facial paralysis (option D), and isolated glossopharyngeal injury (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with penetrating neck trauma develops bubbling air from wound during coughing. This finding strongly suggests:",o:["Thyroid hemorrhage","Communication with airway","Carotid artery rupture","Salivary obstruction","Branchial cyst rupture"],a:1,e:"Air bubbling through neck wound indicates laryngotracheal or tracheal communication. Respiratory distress develops clinically depending on extent of airway disruption.<br><br>Urgent airway protection and surgical exploration may be necessary.<br><br>Thyroid hemorrhage (option A), carotid rupture (option C), salivary obstruction (option D), and branchial rupture (option E) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after blunt neck trauma develops inability to produce high-pitched sounds. The most likely injured structure is the:",o:["Internal laryngeal nerve","Facial nerve","External laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Sympathetic chain"],a:2,e:"The external laryngeal nerve supplies cricothyroid muscle responsible for vocal cord tension. Voice fatigue and reduced pitch develop clinically after injury.<br><br>This deficit may be subtle but important in professional voice users.<br><br>Internal laryngeal nerve (option A), facial nerve (option B), hypoglossal nerve (option D), and sympathetic chain (option E) produce different findings.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe laryngeal edema develops inspiratory stridor because the obstruction is primarily:",o:["Intrathoracic","Alveolar","Extrathoracic upper airway","Pleural","Bronchial distal airway"],a:2,e:"Laryngeal edema narrows the extrathoracic airway causing turbulent inspiratory airflow. High-pitched stridor develops clinically as obstruction worsens.<br><br>This differs from expiratory wheeze seen in lower airway disease.<br><br>Intrathoracic obstruction (option A), alveolar disease (option B), pleural pathology (option D), and distal bronchial disease (option E) produce different sounds.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal trauma develops aspiration pneumonia weeks later. The most likely underlying mechanism is:",o:["Failure of glottic protective closure","Excessive mucus production","Nasal obstruction","Otitis media","Thyroid dysfunction"],a:0,e:"Laryngeal injuries may impair vocal cord mobility and supraglottic closure mechanisms. Recurrent aspiration develops clinically during swallowing leading to pneumonia.<br><br>Swallow rehabilitation is important during recovery.<br><br>Mucus production (option B), nasal obstruction (option C), otitis media (option D), and thyroid dysfunction (option E) are less responsible.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal trauma is unable to phonate effectively because phonation primarily depends upon:",o:["Tracheal rigidity","Nasal airflow only","Vocal cord vibration","Tongue movements exclusively","Thyroid secretion"],a:2,e:"Phonation results from vibration of approximated true vocal cords during expiration. Hoarseness develops clinically after trauma disrupting cord mobility or mucosal integrity.<br><br>Even small vibratory abnormalities may significantly alter voice quality.<br><br>Tracheal rigidity (option A), nasal airflow (option B), tongue movement alone (option D), and thyroid secretion (option E) are less important.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe stridor immediately after extubation following prolonged intubation. The most likely laryngeal injury is:",o:["Subglottic edema","Vocal nodules","Laryngeal papilloma","Branchial fistula","Thyroglossal cyst"],a:0,e:"Prolonged intubation may traumatize subglottic mucosa causing edema and airway narrowing. Inspiratory stridor develops clinically after extubation.<br><br>Children are particularly vulnerable because of narrower subglottic airway.<br><br>Vocal nodules (option B), papilloma (option C), branchial fistula (option D), and thyroglossal cyst (option E) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with blunt laryngeal trauma develops severe dysphonia despite normal airway. The most likely explanation is:",o:["Vocal cord hematoma or edema","Pleural effusion","Nasal septal deviation","Mastoiditis","Sinusitis"],a:0,e:"Even minor trauma affecting vocal cord mucosa alters vibratory characteristics significantly. Hoarseness develops clinically despite preserved airway patency.<br><br>Flexible laryngoscopy helps assess mucosal injury severity.<br><br>Pleural effusion (option B), septal deviation (option C), mastoiditis (option D), and sinusitis (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with penetrating laryngeal trauma develops neck hematoma expanding rapidly. The greatest immediate danger is:",o:["Hearing loss","Facial palsy","Airway compression","Chronic sinusitis","Vocal nodules"],a:2,e:"Expanding cervical hematoma may compress laryngeal airway externally causing acute obstruction. Respiratory distress develops clinically rapidly in severe neck trauma.<br><br>Urgent airway control and hematoma evacuation may be lifesaving.<br><br>Hearing loss (option A), facial palsy (option B), sinusitis (option D), and vocal nodules (option E) are less urgent concerns.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal fracture involving cricoid cartilage is particularly dangerous because the cricoid is:",o:["Incomplete posteriorly","Highly mobile superiorly","Only complete cartilaginous airway ring","Non-supportive structurally","Devoid of mucosa"],a:2,e:"The cricoid forms the only complete cartilaginous ring in upper airway and is crucial for airway stability. Fracture develops clinically with severe airway compromise.<br><br>Subglottic stenosis may occur during healing.<br><br>Incomplete posterior ring (option A), high mobility (option B), lack of support (option D), and absence of mucosa (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with traumatic arytenoid dislocation most commonly presents with:",o:["Persistent hoarseness","Complete aphasia","Bilateral deafness","Facial twitching","Nasal obstruction"],a:0,e:"Arytenoid dislocation impairs normal vocal cord movement and glottic closure. Persistent dysphonia develops clinically after intubation or blunt trauma.<br><br>Laryngoscopic examination confirms abnormal arytenoid position.<br><br>Aphasia (option B), deafness (option C), facial twitching (option D), and nasal obstruction (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe laryngeal trauma undergoes surgical repair. The main long-term goal of reconstruction is preservation of:",o:["Only airway patency","Airway, voice, and swallowing functions","Thyroid hormone production","Facial expression","Eustachian tube function"],a:1,e:"Successful laryngeal reconstruction aims to restore breathing, phonation, and airway protection during swallowing. Chronic aspiration and dysphonia develop clinically after inadequate repair.<br><br>Functional preservation is therefore central to surgical planning.<br><br>Airway alone (option A), thyroid function (option C), facial expression (option D), and Eustachian tube function (option E) are incomplete goals.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops post-intubation posterior glottic stenosis. The primary pathological mechanism is:",o:["Mucosal ischemia and fibrosis","Excess thyroid secretion","Viral papillomatosis","Acute allergy","Facial nerve injury"],a:0,e:"Pressure necrosis from prolonged intubation damages posterior glottic mucosa leading to fibrosis. Progressive hoarseness and airway narrowing develop clinically later.<br><br>Early recognition reduces risk of permanent stenosis.<br><br>Thyroid secretion (option B), papillomatosis (option C), allergy (option D), and facial nerve injury (option E) are unrelated mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with blunt laryngeal trauma develops absent cough reflex above vocal cords. The most likely injured nerve is:",o:["External laryngeal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve only","Internal laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Facial nerve"],a:2,e:"The internal laryngeal nerve provides supraglottic sensation and mediates protective cough reflex. Silent aspiration develops clinically after sensory loss.<br><br>This branch arises from superior laryngeal nerve.<br><br>External laryngeal nerve (option A), recurrent laryngeal nerve alone (option B), hypoglossal nerve (option D), and facial nerve (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe laryngeal trauma develops chronic airway narrowing months later due to:",o:["Subglottic stenosis","Ménière disease","Otosclerosis","Septal perforation","Glossopharyngeal neuralgia"],a:0,e:"Healing after severe laryngeal injury may produce circumferential fibrosis within subglottis. Progressive exertional dyspnea and stridor develop clinically over time.<br><br>Management may require dilation or reconstructive airway surgery.<br><br>Ménière disease (option B), otosclerosis (option C), septal perforation (option D), and glossopharyngeal neuralgia (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A newborn develops inspiratory stridor that worsens during feeding and crying but improves in prone position. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Bilateral choanal atresia","Laryngomalacia","Subglottic stenosis","Vocal cord papilloma","Retropharyngeal abscess"],a:1,e:"Laryngomalacia is the commonest congenital laryngeal anomaly and results from collapse of supraglottic structures during inspiration. Stridor develops clinically within first few weeks of life.<br><br>Symptoms typically worsen during feeding, crying, or supine positioning.<br><br>Choanal atresia (option A), subglottic stenosis (option C), papilloma (option D), and retropharyngeal abscess (option E) differ clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common congenital lesion of larynx is:",o:["Laryngeal web","Laryngocele","Laryngomalacia","Subglottic hemangioma","Congenital cyst"],a:2,e:"Laryngomalacia accounts for the majority of congenital laryngeal anomalies. Inspiratory stridor develops clinically because supraglottic tissues prolapse inward during inspiration.<br><br>Most cases improve spontaneously by 18,24 months of age.<br><br>Laryngeal web (option A), laryngocele (option B), subglottic hemangioma (option D), and congenital cyst (option E) are less common.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with congenital bilateral vocal cord paralysis most dangerously presents with:",o:["Hypernasality","Conductive deafness","Inspiratory stridor and respiratory distress","Epistaxis","Tongue ulceration"],a:2,e:"Bilateral vocal cord paralysis narrows glottic airway critically in infants. Cyanosis and stridor develop clinically soon after birth.<br><br>Airway intervention may become necessary in severe cases.<br><br>Hypernasality (option A), deafness (option B), epistaxis (option D), and tongue ulceration (option E) are unrelated findings.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A neonate with weak cry and aspiration during feeds undergoes laryngoscopy showing unilateral vocal cord immobility. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Congenital unilateral vocal cord paralysis","Choanal atresia","Tracheoesophageal fistula","Retropharyngeal abscess","Croup"],a:0,e:"Congenital unilateral vocal cord paralysis commonly presents with weak cry and aspiration. Feeding difficulty develops clinically because glottic closure becomes ineffective.<br><br>Birth trauma and neurological anomalies are important causes.<br><br>Choanal atresia (option B), tracheoesophageal fistula (option C), retropharyngeal abscess (option D), and croup (option E) differ clinically.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Congenital laryngeal web most commonly occurs at the:",o:["Posterior commissure","Aryepiglottic fold","Anterior glottis","Subglottis only","Pyriform fossa"],a:2,e:"Congenital laryngeal webs usually involve the anterior glottic region because of incomplete recanalization during embryogenesis. Weak cry and airway obstruction develop clinically depending on severity.<br><br>Thin webs may present later with dysphonia alone.<br><br>Posterior commissure (option A), aryepiglottic fold (option B), isolated subglottis (option D), and pyriform fossa (option E) are less common locations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with severe laryngomalacia fails to thrive and develops recurrent cyanotic episodes. The preferred management is:",o:["Observation only","Emergency thyroidectomy","Supraglottoplasty","Radical neck dissection","Radiotherapy"],a:2,e:"Severe laryngomalacia causing feeding difficulty or cyanosis may require surgical correction. Airway obstruction develops clinically because redundant supraglottic tissues collapse inward.<br><br>Supraglottoplasty improves airway patency effectively in symptomatic infants.<br><br>Observation (option A), thyroidectomy (option B), neck dissection (option D), and radiotherapy (option E) are inappropriate.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A neonate with congenital subglottic stenosis most commonly presents with:",o:["Progressive inspiratory stridor","Severe epistaxis","Conductive hearing loss","Facial paralysis","Tongue swelling"],a:0,e:"Congenital narrowing of subglottic airway produces respiratory obstruction early in life. Biphasic stridor develops clinically because the subglottis is the narrowest pediatric airway region.<br><br>Symptoms worsen during respiratory infections.<br><br>Epistaxis (option B), hearing loss (option C), facial paralysis (option D), and tongue swelling (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation most useful for evaluating congenital laryngeal lesions is:",o:["Pure tone audiometry","Sialography","Tympanometry","Flexible or direct laryngoscopy","Thyroid scan"],a:3,e:"Endoscopic examination allows direct visualization of airway anatomy and vocal cord mobility. Stridor develops clinically in most congenital laryngeal lesions.<br><br>Direct laryngoscopy is often combined with bronchoscopy in infants.<br><br>Audiometry (option A), tympanometry (option C), sialography (option B), and thyroid scan (option E) are less useful.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with subglottic hemangioma classically develops:",o:["Biphasic stridor worsening during infancy","Sudden hearing loss","Severe epistaxis","Facial twitching","Tongue paralysis"],a:0,e:"Subglottic hemangiomas proliferate during infancy causing progressive airway narrowing. Biphasic stridor develops clinically with worsening respiratory distress.<br><br>Cutaneous hemangiomas may coexist in some children.<br><br>Hearing loss (option B), epistaxis (option C), facial twitching (option D), and tongue paralysis (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A newborn with laryngeal atresia most likely presents with:",o:["Mild intermittent hoarseness","Nasal obstruction only","Conductive hearing loss","Immediate severe airway obstruction at birth","Facial asymmetry"],a:3,e:"Laryngeal atresia is a rare but life-threatening congenital anomaly causing complete airway obstruction. Absence of cry and cyanosis develop clinically immediately after birth.<br><br>Emergency airway establishment is required for survival.<br><br>Mild hoarseness (option A), hearing loss (option C), nasal obstruction (option B), and facial asymmetry (option E) are less typical.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with congenital laryngeal cyst most commonly presents with:",o:["Inspiratory stridor and feeding difficulty","Bilateral deafness","Epistaxis","Facial swelling","Chronic otorrhea"],a:0,e:"Congenital laryngeal cysts may obstruct supraglottic airway in infants. Stridor and poor feeding develop clinically because of airway narrowing.<br><br>Endoscopic marsupialization is commonly required.<br><br>Deafness (option B), epistaxis (option C), facial swelling (option D), and chronic otorrhea (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The pathophysiological mechanism of laryngomalacia is primarily:",o:["Rigid supraglottic cartilages","Dynamic inspiratory collapse of supraglottic structures","Vocal cord paralysis","Fixed subglottic obstruction","Tracheoesophageal fistula"],a:1,e:"Flaccid supraglottic tissues collapse inward during inspiration due to negative airway pressure. Inspiratory stridor develops clinically in early infancy.<br><br>Omega-shaped epiglottis is a common endoscopic finding.<br><br>Rigid cartilages (option A), vocal cord paralysis (option C), fixed obstruction (option D), and fistula (option E) are different mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with congenital bilateral vocal cord paralysis requires urgent tracheostomy because the cords usually lie in:",o:["Fully abducted position","Vertical position","Extreme lateral position","Intermediate or paramedian position","Oscillating mobile position"],a:3,e:"Paramedian vocal cord position severely narrows neonatal airway. Inspiratory stridor and cyanosis develop clinically in bilateral paralysis.<br><br>Voice may remain relatively preserved despite respiratory compromise.<br><br>Fully abducted cords (option A), extreme lateral position (option C), vertical orientation (option B), and oscillating mobility (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with laryngeal web presents mainly with:",o:["Weak cry and airway obstruction","Conductive hearing loss","Severe vertigo","Facial palsy","Otalgia"],a:0,e:"Laryngeal webs restrict normal glottic opening and alter vocal cord vibration. Weak cry and stridor develop clinically depending on web thickness.<br><br>Anterior glottic webs are the commonest type.<br><br>Hearing loss (option B), vertigo (option C), facial palsy (option D), and otalgia (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Congenital subglottic stenosis becomes clinically significant because the pediatric subglottis is:",o:["Richly vascular only","Structurally rigid in all directions","Lined by squamous epithelium exclusively","The narrowest portion of infant airway","Devoid of cartilage"],a:3,e:"Even minimal edema markedly reduces airway caliber in infants because the subglottis is naturally narrow. Biphasic stridor develops clinically in congenital stenosis.<br><br>Respiratory infections may precipitate acute deterioration.<br><br>Rich vascularity (option A), exclusive squamous lining (option C), rigidity (option B), and absent cartilage (option E) are incorrect explanations.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with subglottic hemangioma is increasingly cyanotic despite steroids. The most effective modern therapy is:",o:["Radiotherapy","Oral propranolol","Radical neck dissection","Mastoidectomy","Septoplasty"],a:1,e:"Propranolol causes involution of infantile hemangiomas and improves airway obstruction. Progressive stridor develops clinically during hemangioma proliferation phase.<br><br>This treatment has largely replaced older therapies like radiotherapy.<br><br>Radiotherapy (option A), neck dissection (option C), mastoidectomy (option D), and septoplasty (option E) are inappropriate.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A neonate with congenital laryngeal anomaly develops recurrent aspiration pneumonia because of impaired:",o:["Olfactory function","Vestibular function","Eustachian tube drainage","Airway protective mechanisms","Salivary secretion"],a:3,e:"Congenital laryngeal abnormalities may impair glottic closure and supraglottic protection. Aspiration develops clinically during feeding leading to recurrent chest infections.<br><br>Swallow evaluation is important in affected infants.<br><br>Olfaction (option A), Eustachian tube function (option C), vestibular function (option B), and salivation (option E) are less relevant.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"An omega-shaped epiglottis is classically associated with:",o:["Vocal cord paralysis","Laryngeal papilloma","Subglottic stenosis","Laryngomalacia","Choanal atresia"],a:3,e:"An omega-shaped epiglottis is a typical endoscopic finding in laryngomalacia. Inspiratory collapse of supraglottic tissues develops clinically during inspiration.<br><br>Flexible laryngoscopy confirms the diagnosis.<br><br>Vocal cord paralysis (option A), subglottic stenosis (option C), papilloma (option B), and choanal atresia (option E) lack this feature.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with severe congenital subglottic stenosis fails extubation repeatedly. Definitive management may require:",o:["Cochlear implant","Radical neck dissection","Tympanoplasty","Laryngotracheal reconstruction","Tonsillectomy only"],a:3,e:"Severe congenital subglottic stenosis may require airway expansion procedures using cartilage grafts. Persistent stridor and extubation failure develop clinically in severe disease.<br><br>The aim is restoration of stable airway without tracheostomy dependence.<br><br>Cochlear implantation (option A), tympanoplasty (option C), neck dissection (option B), and tonsillectomy (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A newborn with congenital laryngeal cyst undergoes endoscopic marsupialization primarily to:",o:["Improve hearing","Relieve airway obstruction","Correct facial asymmetry","Prevent epistaxis","Treat sinusitis"],a:1,e:"Laryngeal cysts obstruct narrow infant airway causing stridor and feeding difficulty. Respiratory distress develops clinically in larger lesions.<br><br>Endoscopic decompression restores airway patency effectively.<br><br>Hearing improvement (option A), facial correction (option C), prevention of epistaxis (option D), and sinusitis treatment (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"Congenital unilateral vocal cord paralysis in infants is commonly associated with:",o:["Intracranial or birth trauma-related neurological injury","Chronic otitis media","Nasal polyposis","Ménière disease","Septal hematoma"],a:0,e:"Neurological abnormalities and difficult delivery may injure vagal pathways causing congenital vocal cord paralysis. Weak cry and aspiration develop clinically.<br><br>Many cases require multidisciplinary neurological evaluation.<br><br>Otitis media (option B), nasal polyposis (option C), Ménière disease (option D), and septal hematoma (option E) are unrelated associations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with laryngomalacia is managed conservatively because most cases:",o:["Progress to malignancy","Require radiotherapy eventually","Cause permanent aphonia","Resolve spontaneously with laryngeal maturation","Lead to bilateral paralysis"],a:3,e:"Most infants improve as laryngeal tone and cartilage rigidity increase during growth. Inspiratory stridor develops clinically early but gradually subsides.<br><br>Observation is appropriate in mild uncomplicated disease.<br><br>Malignant transformation (option A), permanent aphonia (option C), radiotherapy need (option B), and bilateral paralysis (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with congenital laryngeal web undergoes surgical division. The major postoperative concern is:",o:["Hearing loss","Vertigo","Facial paralysis","Web recurrence and glottic scarring","Chronic sinusitis"],a:3,e:"Surgical division may lead to re-adhesion and fibrosis within anterior commissure. Persistent dysphonia develops clinically after recurrent web formation.<br><br>Silastic keel placement may reduce recurrence risk.<br><br>Hearing loss (option A), facial paralysis (option C), vertigo (option B), and sinusitis (option E) are unrelated concerns.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with congenital subglottic stenosis presents with biphasic rather than inspiratory-only stridor because:",o:["Obstruction lies at fixed central airway level","Nasal cavity is involved","Vocal cords overabduct","Lung parenchyma collapses","Pleural pressure rises excessively"],a:0,e:"Fixed lesions at subglottic level obstruct airflow during both inspiration and expiration. Biphasic stridor develops clinically in congenital subglottic stenosis.<br><br>Inspiratory-only stridor is more typical of supraglottic collapse.<br><br>Nasal involvement (option B), overabduction (option C), lung collapse (option D), and pleural pressure changes (option E) are less relevant.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A neonate with severe airway obstruction at birth undergoes emergency airway access. The preferred definitive airway in congenital laryngeal obstruction is often:",o:["Nasal packing","Tympanostomy","Septoplasty","Tracheostomy","Cricothyrotomy"],a:3,e:"Severe congenital laryngeal obstruction may require tracheostomy for stable long-term airway maintenance. Cyanosis and respiratory distress develop clinically immediately after birth.<br><br>Cricothyrotomy is generally avoided in infants because of small anatomy.<br><br>Nasal packing (option A), septoplasty (option C), tympanostomy (option B), and cricothyrotomy (option E) are less suitable.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with congenital laryngeal anomaly develops chronic feeding difficulty and poor weight gain. The mechanism is most likely:",o:["Increased salivation only","Nasal obstruction exclusively","Hyperthyroidism","Increased caloric expenditure and aspiration during feeding","Vestibular dysfunction"],a:3,e:"Infants with chronic airway obstruction expend more energy during breathing and may aspirate feeds. Failure to thrive develops clinically in severe laryngeal lesions.<br><br>Feeding support becomes important in management.<br><br>Salivation alone (option A), hyperthyroidism (option C), isolated nasal obstruction (option B), and vestibular dysfunction (option E) are less important.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"Congenital laryngeal lesions are best assessed dynamically during spontaneous breathing because:",o:["Static imaging alone detects all abnormalities","CT scan replaces endoscopy entirely","Vocal cords remain fixed in infants","Dynamic collapse may only appear during inspiration","Swallowing cannot be assessed clinically"],a:3,e:"Conditions such as laryngomalacia are dynamic lesions becoming evident only during inspiratory airflow. Stridor develops clinically due to airway collapse.<br><br>Flexible laryngoscopy during awake breathing therefore provides important diagnostic information.<br><br>Static imaging (option A), fixed cords (option C), CT replacement (option B), and inability to assess swallowing (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with congenital laryngeal anomaly develops repeated cyanotic episodes during feeding. The immediate priority is:",o:["Audiometry","Airway and feeding stabilization","Tympanometry","Sinus surgery","Neck dissection"],a:1,e:"Recurrent cyanotic episodes indicate potentially life-threatening airway compromise and aspiration. Respiratory distress develops clinically during feeding in severe congenital lesions.<br><br>Urgent airway assessment and nutritional support are essential.<br><br>Audiometry (option A), tympanometry (option C), sinus surgery (option D), and neck dissection (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with congenital laryngeal lesion develops persistent hoarseness without severe stridor. The lesion most likely involves the:",o:["Supraglottis only","Pyriform fossa exclusively","Nasopharynx","Glottic region affecting vocal cord vibration","Trachea alone"],a:3,e:"Glottic lesions interfere directly with vocal cord vibration and phonation. Persistent dysphonia develops clinically even when airway compromise is mild.<br><br>Laryngeal webs commonly present this way.<br><br>Supraglottic lesions (option A), nasopharyngeal lesions (option C), pyriform lesions (option B), and isolated tracheal lesions (option E) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with severe congenital laryngeal obstruction is found to have associated cardiac and neurological anomalies. This association is clinically important because it:",o:["Excludes airway surgery completely","Guarantees spontaneous recovery","Prevents endoscopic evaluation","Influences prognosis and multidisciplinary management","Indicates malignancy"],a:3,e:"Congenital laryngeal anomalies frequently coexist with systemic abnormalities. Feeding difficulty and developmental issues develop clinically in complex syndromic children.<br><br>Comprehensive multidisciplinary care is therefore essential for optimal outcomes.<br><br>Exclusion of surgery (option A), inability to perform endoscopy (option C), guaranteed recovery (option B), and malignancy (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 58-year-old smoker presents with persistent hoarseness for 4 months without pain. Which diagnosis must be excluded first?",o:["Acute laryngitis","Vocal cord cyst","Laryngeal carcinoma","Reinke edema","Vocal abuse"],a:2,e:"Persistent hoarseness in smokers is malignant until proven otherwise. Early glottic cancers present clinically with isolated voice change because even small lesions affect vocal cord vibration.<br><br>Flexible laryngoscopy is mandatory in prolonged unexplained hoarseness.<br><br>Acute laryngitis (option A), vocal cyst (option B), Reinke edema (option D), and vocal abuse (option E) are possible but less dangerous causes.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Hoarseness occurring after thyroidectomy most commonly results from injury to the:",o:["Facial nerve","Internal laryngeal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:2,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve supplies intrinsic laryngeal muscles responsible for vocal cord movement. Hoarseness develops clinically after unilateral paralysis due to incomplete glottic closure.<br><br>Bilateral injury may produce airway compromise and stridor.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), internal laryngeal nerve (option B), glossopharyngeal nerve (option D), and hypoglossal nerve (option E) produce different deficits.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A teacher with gradually progressive hoarseness and bilateral symmetrical vocal cord swellings most likely has:",o:["Vocal nodules","Glottic carcinoma","Vocal cord paralysis","Laryngeal papilloma","Subglottic stenosis"],a:0,e:"Vocal nodules occur due to chronic phonotrauma and commonly affect professional voice users. Hoarseness develops clinically with bilateral symmetrical lesions at junction of anterior and middle thirds.<br><br>Voice therapy remains the primary treatment.<br><br>Glottic carcinoma (option B), paralysis (option C), papilloma (option D), and subglottic stenosis (option E) differ clinically.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy most commonly demonstrates the affected vocal cord in:",o:["Fully abducted position","Vertical orientation","Extreme adduction","Paramedian position","Oscillating motion"],a:3,e:"Denervated cords usually rest near the paramedian position because of preserved cricothyroid muscle tone. Hoarseness develops clinically due to incomplete glottic closure.<br><br>Compensation by the opposite cord may improve voice quality over time.<br><br>Full abduction (option A), extreme adduction (option C), vertical orientation (option B), and oscillation (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with hoarseness and aspiration after skull base surgery most likely has injury to the:",o:["Facial nerve","Sympathetic chain","Lingual nerve","Vagus nerve","Accessory nerve"],a:3,e:"The vagus nerve supplies recurrent and superior laryngeal branches responsible for phonation and airway protection. Hoarseness and aspiration develop clinically after high vagal injury.<br><br>Flexible laryngoscopy commonly reveals vocal cord paralysis.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), lingual nerve (option C), sympathetic chain (option B), and accessory nerve (option E) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A singer develops inability to produce high-pitched notes after thyroid surgery. The most likely injured nerve is:",o:["Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Internal laryngeal nerve","External laryngeal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Facial nerve"],a:2,e:"The external laryngeal nerve supplies cricothyroid muscle which tenses vocal cords. Voice fatigue and loss of high-pitched phonation develop clinically after injury.<br><br>Professional voice users notice this deficit particularly early.<br><br>Recurrent laryngeal nerve (option A), internal laryngeal nerve (option B), glossopharyngeal nerve (option D), and facial nerve (option E) are less responsible.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation of choice for evaluating persistent hoarseness is:",o:["Pure tone audiometry","Flexible laryngoscopy","Tympanometry","CT brain","Sialography"],a:1,e:"Flexible laryngoscopy permits direct visualization of vocal cord mobility and mucosal lesions. Persistent dysphonia develops clinically in multiple laryngeal pathologies.<br><br>It is the primary outpatient assessment tool for hoarseness.<br><br>Audiometry (option A), tympanometry (option C), CT brain (option D), and sialography (option E) are less appropriate initial tests.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with sudden hoarseness following upper respiratory infection most likely has:",o:["Acute laryngitis","Vocal cord carcinoma","Arytenoid dislocation","Laryngeal tuberculosis","Subglottic stenosis"],a:0,e:"Acute viral laryngitis commonly produces sudden transient hoarseness following respiratory tract infection. Vocal cord edema develops clinically causing impaired vibration.<br><br>Symptoms usually improve with voice rest and hydration.<br><br>Carcinoma (option B), arytenoid dislocation (option C), tuberculosis (option D), and stenosis (option E) are less acute.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with progressive hoarseness and hemoptysis undergoes biopsy showing squamous cell carcinoma. The commonest site of laryngeal cancer is the:",o:["Subglottis","Supraglottis","Glottis","Aryepiglottic fold only","Pyriform fossa"],a:2,e:"Glottic cancers are the commonest laryngeal malignancies and present early with hoarseness. Persistent voice change develops clinically because true vocal cord vibration becomes impaired.<br><br>Early presentation contributes to relatively favorable prognosis.<br><br>Subglottis (option A), supraglottis (option B), aryepiglottic fold (option D), and pyriform fossa (option E) are less common sites.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with recurrent hoarseness and wart-like lesions on vocal cords most likely has:",o:["Vocal nodules","Recurrent respiratory papillomatosis","Laryngeal carcinoma","Vocal cord palsy","Laryngeal web"],a:1,e:"Human papillomavirus-related papillomas cause recurrent exophytic vocal cord lesions. Progressive hoarseness develops clinically and airway obstruction may occur in severe disease.<br><br>Repeated microlaryngoscopic debulking procedures are commonly required.<br><br>Vocal nodules (option A), carcinoma (option C), palsy (option D), and laryngeal web (option E) differ clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with hoarseness and left vocal cord paralysis should be evaluated for mediastinal pathology because the left recurrent laryngeal nerve loops around the:",o:["Subclavian artery","Pulmonary vein","Carotid bifurcation","Arch of aorta","Vertebral artery"],a:3,e:"The left recurrent laryngeal nerve descends into thorax before looping around aortic arch. Hoarseness develops clinically in mediastinal malignancies compressing the nerve.<br><br>Chest imaging is therefore important in unexplained left vocal cord palsy.<br><br>Subclavian artery (option A), carotid bifurcation (option C), pulmonary vein (option B), and vertebral artery (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with psychogenic hoarseness most commonly demonstrates:",o:["Complete structural vocal cord destruction","Severe airway obstruction","Bilateral vocal cord fixation","Normal cough despite aphonia","Ulcerative laryngeal lesions"],a:3,e:"Psychogenic aphonia presents with impaired speech but preserved involuntary vocalization such as coughing. Emotional stress commonly contributes clinically to symptom development.<br><br>Laryngoscopy usually reveals structurally normal cords.<br><br>Structural destruction (option A), bilateral fixation (option C), airway obstruction (option B), and ulcerative lesions (option E) are less typical.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic smoking and low-pitched rough voice but no discrete lesion most likely has:",o:["Reinke edema","Acute epiglottitis","Vocal cord paralysis","Laryngeal web","Subglottic stenosis"],a:0,e:"Smoking-related fluid accumulation within superficial lamina propria produces Reinke edema. Deep husky voice develops clinically especially in female smokers.<br><br>Smoking cessation and microlaryngeal surgery may improve symptoms.<br><br>Epiglottitis (option B), paralysis (option C), laryngeal web (option D), and stenosis (option E) differ clinically.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops persistent hoarseness after prolonged endotracheal intubation. The most likely lesion is:",o:["Vocal cord nodule","Intubation granuloma","Glottic carcinoma","Laryngocele","Choanal atresia"],a:1,e:"Pressure injury over vocal process during prolonged intubation may produce contact granulomas. Persistent hoarseness develops clinically with throat discomfort.<br><br>Voice abuse and reflux may worsen lesion persistence.<br><br>Vocal nodules (option A), carcinoma (option C), laryngocele (option D), and choanal atresia (option E) are less related.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral vocal cord paralysis most critically develops:",o:["Hypernasality","Facial asymmetry","Complete aphasia only","Inspiratory stridor","Conductive hearing loss"],a:3,e:"Bilateral immobile cords narrow the glottic airway critically. Stridor and respiratory distress develop clinically because cords fail to abduct adequately.<br><br>Emergency airway intervention may become necessary.<br><br>Hypernasality (option A), aphasia (option C), facial asymmetry (option B), and hearing loss (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral vocal cord paralysis undergoes medialization thyroplasty primarily to improve:",o:["Hearing","Vestibular function","Nasal airflow","Glottic closure during phonation","Salivation"],a:3,e:"Medialization procedures reposition the paralyzed cord toward midline improving voice quality. Breathy hoarseness develops clinically due to incomplete glottic closure.<br><br>Swallowing may also improve after surgery.<br><br>Hearing (option A), nasal airflow (option C), vestibular function (option B), and salivation (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with hoarseness and painful swallowing has irregular ulcerative supraglottic lesion. Compared with glottic cancer, supraglottic tumors commonly:",o:["Present earlier with hoarseness","Never cause dysphagia","Lack lymphatic drainage","Metastasize earlier to cervical nodes","Spare epiglottis"],a:3,e:"The supraglottis possesses rich lymphatic drainage promoting early nodal spread. Dysphagia and neck masses develop clinically before severe hoarseness.<br><br>This contrasts with sparse lymphatics of true vocal cords.<br><br>Earlier hoarseness (option A), absent lymphatics (option C), absence of dysphagia (option B), and epiglottic sparing (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with muscle tension dysphonia usually demonstrates:",o:["Excessive laryngeal muscular activity without structural lesion","Bilateral vocal cord paralysis","Laryngeal carcinoma","Subglottic stenosis","Vocal cord papilloma"],a:0,e:"Muscle tension dysphonia results from abnormal laryngeal muscle use during phonation. Hoarseness develops clinically despite structurally normal vocal cords.<br><br>Voice therapy is the main treatment approach.<br><br>Paralysis (option B), carcinoma (option C), stenosis (option D), and papilloma (option E) are different disorders.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent hoarseness and chronic cough has posterior laryngeal erythema on laryngoscopy. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Laryngopharyngeal reflux","Vocal cord palsy","Glottic carcinoma","Laryngeal web","Acute epiglottitis"],a:0,e:"Acid reflux may inflame posterior laryngeal mucosa causing chronic dysphonia and throat clearing. Posterior commissure erythema develops clinically on endoscopy.<br><br>Lifestyle modification and proton pump inhibitors are commonly used.<br><br>Vocal palsy (option B), carcinoma (option C), laryngeal web (option D), and epiglottitis (option E) differ clinically.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with hoarseness after anterior cervical spine surgery most likely has injury to the:",o:["Facial nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Lingual nerve","Trigeminal nerve","Accessory nerve"],a:1,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve is vulnerable during anterior neck procedures. Hoarseness develops clinically because vocal cord mobility becomes impaired.<br><br>Laryngoscopy confirms postoperative vocal cord paralysis.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), lingual nerve (option C), trigeminal nerve (option D), and accessory nerve (option E) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral vocal cord paralysis has breathy voice because:",o:["Excess mucus production occurs","Nasal airflow is blocked","Vocal cords are hyperadducted","Incomplete glottic closure permits air escape","Pharyngeal muscles are paralyzed completely"],a:3,e:"Paralyzed cords fail to approximate effectively during phonation causing air leakage. Breathy dysphonia develops clinically with weak cough.<br><br>Aspiration may also occur in severe cases.<br><br>Mucus production (option A), hyperadduction (option C), nasal blockage (option B), and total pharyngeal paralysis (option E) are less responsible.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with sudden hoarseness immediately after difficult intubation most likely has:",o:["Arytenoid dislocation","Vocal nodule","Reinke edema","Glottic carcinoma","Vocal cord papilloma"],a:0,e:"Traumatic intubation may displace arytenoid cartilage causing impaired vocal cord movement. Persistent hoarseness develops clinically soon after extubation.<br><br>Laryngoscopy demonstrates asymmetrical arytenoid positioning.<br><br>Vocal nodules (option B), Reinke edema (option C), carcinoma (option D), and papilloma (option E) are less acute.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest symptom of early glottic carcinoma is:",o:["Neck swelling","Hematemesis","Dysphagia","Persistent hoarseness","Otalgia"],a:3,e:"Small glottic lesions impair normal vocal cord vibration early in disease. Persistent dysphonia develops clinically before nodal spread occurs.<br><br>Early presentation contributes to favorable survival outcomes.<br><br>Neck swelling (option A), dysphagia (option C), hematemesis (option B), and otalgia (option E) occur later or less commonly.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent respiratory papillomatosis most commonly acquires the causative virus through:",o:["Airborne fungal spores","Epstein-Barr virus","Tuberculous infection","Vertical HPV transmission","Fecal-oral contamination"],a:3,e:"Juvenile recurrent respiratory papillomatosis is associated with HPV types 6 and 11. Progressive hoarseness develops clinically due to recurrent papillomatous growths.<br><br>Vertical maternal transmission during birth is a recognized mechanism.<br><br>Fungal spores (option A), tuberculosis (option C), Epstein-Barr virus (option B), and fecal-oral spread (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral vocal cord paralysis and no neck pathology should undergo chest imaging mainly to evaluate the:",o:["Apex of lung and mediastinum","Liver","Middle ear","Maxillary sinus","Salivary glands"],a:0,e:"Thoracic lesions may compress the recurrent laryngeal nerve, particularly on the left side. Hoarseness develops clinically in apical lung or mediastinal tumors.<br><br>Chest imaging is therefore essential in unexplained vocal cord palsy.<br><br>Liver (option B), middle ear (option C), maxillary sinus (option D), and salivary glands (option E) are less relevant.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic hoarseness is found to have leukoplakia of vocal cord. The major clinical concern is:",o:["Ménière disease","Acute epiglottitis","Conductive hearing loss","Premalignant potential","Facial paralysis"],a:3,e:"Leukoplakia may harbor dysplasia or early carcinoma within vocal cord epithelium. Persistent hoarseness develops clinically due to mucosal abnormality.<br><br>Biopsy is important for histopathological assessment.<br><br>Ménière disease (option A), hearing loss (option C), epiglottitis (option B), and facial paralysis (option E) are unrelated concerns.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral vocal cord paralysis but relatively preserved voice demonstrates respiratory distress because the cords remain:",o:["Too lateralized","Hypermobile","Completely absent","Near midline obstructing airflow","Scarred posteriorly only"],a:3,e:"Bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy leaves cords near paramedian position. Airway narrowing develops clinically causing stridor despite acceptable phonation.<br><br>This paradoxical combination is characteristic.<br><br>Excessive lateralization (option A), absent cords (option C), hypermobility (option B), and isolated posterior scarring (option E) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic voice abuse develops small bilateral lesions at junction of anterior one-third and posterior two-thirds of vocal cords. These are:",o:["Vocal nodules","Contact ulcers","Intubation granulomas","Laryngeal cysts","Polyps"],a:0,e:"Vocal nodules arise at the point of maximal vibratory trauma during phonation. Progressive hoarseness develops clinically in professional voice users.<br><br>Lesions are typically bilateral and symmetrical.<br><br>Contact ulcers (option B), granulomas (option C), cysts (option D), and polyps (option E) differ in site and morphology.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral vocal cord paralysis develops recurrent aspiration. Which maneuver may temporarily improve swallowing safety?",o:["Chin tuck during swallowing","Hyperextension of neck","Mouth breathing only","Valsalva during inspiration","Jaw protrusion"],a:0,e:"Postural swallowing maneuvers may reduce aspiration risk in glottic incompetence. Coughing during feeds develops clinically in unilateral vocal cord paralysis.<br><br>Speech and swallow therapy are important components of management.<br><br>Neck hyperextension (option B), mouth breathing (option C), inspiratory Valsalva (option D), and jaw protrusion (option E) are less helpful.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with hoarseness and mobile smooth unilateral vocal cord swelling most likely has a vocal cord polyp because polyps are usually:",o:["Bilateral and symmetrical","Unilateral lesions related to phonotrauma","Malignant by default","Fixed infiltrative masses","Associated with vocal cord paralysis"],a:1,e:"Vocal polyps commonly arise after acute vocal abuse or chronic phonotrauma. Persistent hoarseness develops clinically because the lesion disrupts normal mucosal wave vibration.<br><br>Microlaryngoscopic excision may be required when voice therapy alone fails.<br><br>Bilateral symmetry (option A), mandatory malignancy (option C), infiltrative fixation (option D), and association with paralysis (option E) are less typical.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 62-year-old smoker presents with progressive hoarseness for 5 months. Laryngoscopy reveals a small lesion confined to one true vocal cord with normal mobility and no cervical lymphadenopathy. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Early glottic carcinoma","Supraglottic carcinoma","Laryngeal papillomatosis","Vocal cord granuloma","Subglottic stenosis"],a:0,e:"Early glottic cancers commonly present with isolated persistent hoarseness because true vocal cords are essential for phonation. Nodal metastasis develops clinically less frequently due to sparse lymphatic drainage.<br><br>Preserved cord mobility suggests early-stage disease with favorable prognosis.<br><br>Supraglottic carcinoma (option B), papillomatosis (option C), granuloma (option D), and stenosis (option E) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest histological type of laryngeal malignancy is:",o:["Adenocarcinoma","Lymphoma","Chondrosarcoma","Squamous cell carcinoma","Melanoma"],a:3,e:"Squamous cell carcinoma accounts for the overwhelming majority of laryngeal cancers. Smoking and alcohol consumption contribute significantly to disease development clinically.<br><br>Most tumors arise from mucosal epithelium lining the larynx.<br><br>Adenocarcinoma (option A), chondrosarcoma (option C), lymphoma (option B), and melanoma (option E) are uncommon.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with supraglottic carcinoma is more likely than glottic carcinoma to present with:",o:["Early isolated hoarseness","Facial nerve palsy","Bilateral deafness","Cervical lymph node metastasis","Vertigo"],a:3,e:"The supraglottis possesses rich lymphatic drainage promoting early nodal spread. Dysphagia and neck masses develop clinically before marked hoarseness appears.<br><br>This contrasts with sparse lymphatics of true vocal cords.<br><br>Early isolated hoarseness (option A), deafness (option C), facial palsy (option B), and vertigo (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation of choice for initial assessment of persistent hoarseness is:",o:["Pure tone audiometry","Barium swallow only","Tympanometry","Flexible laryngoscopy","CT brain"],a:3,e:"Flexible laryngoscopy permits direct visualization of laryngeal mucosa and vocal cord mobility. Persistent dysphonia develops clinically early in laryngeal malignancy.<br><br>It is the essential first outpatient investigation for suspected laryngeal tumors.<br><br>Audiometry (option A), tympanometry (option C), barium swallow (option B), and CT brain (option E) are less appropriate initially.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced laryngeal carcinoma develops inspiratory stridor because the tumor causes:",o:["Lower airway fibrosis","Pleural effusion","Diaphragmatic paralysis","Glottic airway obstruction","Bronchiectasis"],a:3,e:"Progressive tumor growth narrows the laryngeal airway causing turbulent inspiratory airflow. Stridor develops clinically in advanced obstructive lesions.<br><br>Airway stabilization may become urgently necessary.<br><br>Lower airway fibrosis (option A), diaphragmatic paralysis (option C), pleural effusion (option B), and bronchiectasis (option E) are less responsible.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 58-year-old chronic smoker presents with progressive hoarseness, mild hemoptysis, and left-sided referred otalgia. Flexible laryngoscopy reveals ulcerative supraglottic lesion involving aryepiglottic fold with ipsilateral level II cervical node enlargement. Which anatomical feature explains the early nodal metastasis?",o:["Sparse lymphatic drainage of glottis","Rich supraglottic lymphatic network","Bilateral recurrent laryngeal innervation","Cricoid cartilage continuity","Poor vascularity of epiglottis"],a:1,e:"The supraglottic larynx possesses abundant lymphatic channels that facilitate early cervical nodal spread. Dysphagia and neck masses develop clinically before severe airway compromise.<br><br>This differs significantly from glottic tumors which metastasize later because of sparse lymphatic drainage.<br><br>Sparse glottic lymphatics (option A), recurrent nerve supply (option C), cricoid continuity (option D), and epiglottic vascularity (option E) are less relevant.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with T1 glottic carcinoma and preserved vocal cord mobility is commonly managed with:",o:["Total laryngectomy only","Radical neck dissection only","Radiotherapy or endoscopic laser excision","Chemotherapy alone","Thyroidectomy"],a:2,e:"Early glottic cancers are highly curable with organ-preserving treatment modalities. Persistent hoarseness develops clinically early, allowing diagnosis before nodal spread occurs.<br><br>Voice preservation is an important consideration in treatment selection.<br><br>Total laryngectomy (option A), neck dissection alone (option B), chemotherapy alone (option D), and thyroidectomy (option E) are inappropriate.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest site of laryngeal carcinoma is the:",o:["Subglottis","Aryepiglottic fold","Glottis","Posterior commissure","Pyriform fossa"],a:2,e:"Glottic carcinomas account for the majority of laryngeal cancers. Persistent hoarseness develops clinically early because lesions interfere with vocal cord vibration.<br><br>Early presentation contributes to relatively favorable prognosis.<br><br>Subglottis (option A), aryepiglottic fold (option B), posterior commissure (option D), and pyriform fossa (option E) are less common sites.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal carcinoma develops fixation of vocal cord. This finding usually indicates:",o:["Benign vocal nodule","Deep infiltration involving intrinsic muscles or joint","Acute laryngitis","Psychogenic dysphonia","Simple mucosal edema"],a:1,e:"Cord fixation suggests advanced tumor extension into intrinsic laryngeal musculature or cricoarytenoid joint. Progressive hoarseness and airway symptoms develop clinically.<br><br>This finding upgrades tumor staging significantly.<br><br>Vocal nodules (option A), laryngitis (option C), psychogenic causes (option D), and mucosal edema (option E) do not typically fix cords.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with glottic carcinoma has relatively good prognosis mainly because:",o:["Tumors are painless","Cervical nodes are absent anatomically","Subglottis blocks spread completely","Hoarseness leads to early diagnosis","Glottis lacks blood supply"],a:3,e:"Small glottic lesions impair phonation early because vocal cord vibration becomes abnormal. Persistent dysphonia develops clinically before extensive spread occurs.<br><br>Early detection contributes substantially to survival outcomes.<br><br>Painlessness (option A), subglottic barrier (option C), absent nodes (option B), and lack of blood supply (option E) are incorrect explanations.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal carcinoma undergoes direct laryngoscopy and biopsy primarily to:",o:["Measure hearing thresholds","Detect sinusitis","Assess vestibular function","Confirm histopathological diagnosis","Evaluate thyroid hormone levels"],a:3,e:"Definitive diagnosis of laryngeal cancer requires histological confirmation. Hoarseness and dysphagia develop clinically depending on tumor site and extent.<br><br>Direct laryngoscopy permits visualization and targeted biopsy of suspicious lesions.<br><br>Hearing assessment (option A), vestibular testing (option C), sinus evaluation (option B), and thyroid studies (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with supraglottic carcinoma complains of referred ear pain because of shared sensory supply through the:",o:["Facial nerve","Sympathetic chain only","Hypoglossal nerve","Glossopharyngeal and vagal pathways","Accessory nerve"],a:3,e:"The larynx and external auditory canal share cranial nerve sensory pathways causing referred otalgia. Dysphagia and throat pain develop clinically in supraglottic tumors.<br><br>Referred ear pain is an important red-flag symptom in head and neck cancer.<br><br>Facial nerve (option A), hypoglossal nerve (option C), sympathetic chain (option B), and accessory nerve (option E) are less involved.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced laryngeal carcinoma undergoes total laryngectomy. The permanent stoma is created because:",o:["The entire larynx is removed from airway continuity","The vocal cords regenerate poorly","Salivary glands are excised","The esophagus is disconnected permanently","Trachea becomes functionless"],a:0,e:"Total laryngectomy separates the airway permanently from upper aerodigestive tract. Breathing occurs clinically through a permanent tracheostoma after surgery.<br><br>Voice rehabilitation becomes an important postoperative objective.<br><br>Poor cord regeneration (option B), salivary excision (option C), esophageal disconnection (option D), and tracheal dysfunction (option E) are incorrect explanations.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after total laryngectomy is most likely to lose the ability to:",o:["Swallow saliva completely","Move tongue","Taste food","Produce normal laryngeal voice","Breathe independently"],a:3,e:"Removal of vocal cords eliminates natural phonation after laryngectomy. Aphonia develops clinically unless alternative speech rehabilitation methods are used.<br><br>Esophageal speech and tracheoesophageal prostheses may restore communication.<br><br>Swallowing saliva (option A), taste (option C), tongue movement (option B), and independent breathing (option E) may remain preserved.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with subglottic carcinoma often presents late because the subglottis:",o:["Is richly innervated for pain","Produces early hoarseness","Allows silent tumor growth initially","Lacks mucosal lining","Causes immediate airway obstruction"],a:2,e:"Subglottic tumors may enlarge significantly before causing symptoms. Progressive airway compromise develops clinically relatively late compared with glottic lesions.<br><br>Delayed presentation contributes to poorer prognosis.<br><br>Rich pain innervation (option A), early hoarseness (option B), absent mucosa (option D), and immediate obstruction (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old smoker presents with progressive hoarseness, weight loss, dysphagia, and stridor. CT scan demonstrates transglottic carcinoma with thyroid cartilage invasion and bilateral cervical lymphadenopathy. Which management is most appropriate?",o:["Observation only","Voice therapy alone","Total laryngectomy with neck dissection","Tonsillectomy only","Nasal packing"],a:2,e:"Advanced transglottic tumors with cartilage invasion usually require radical surgical management. Airway obstruction and dysphagia develop clinically in extensive disease.<br><br>Cervical nodal metastases also require therapeutic neck dissection.<br><br>Observation (option A), voice therapy (option B), tonsillectomy (option D), and nasal packing (option E) are inappropriate.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent laryngeal carcinoma after radiotherapy develops severe airway compromise. The salvage procedure most commonly required is:",o:["Tympanoplasty","Cochlear implantation","Septoplasty","Salvage total laryngectomy","Thyroid lobectomy"],a:3,e:"Persistent or recurrent disease after organ-preserving therapy often requires definitive surgical excision. Stridor and aspiration develop clinically in advanced recurrent tumors.<br><br>Previous radiation increases operative complexity and wound complications.<br><br>Tympanoplasty (option A), septoplasty (option C), cochlear implantation (option B), and thyroid surgery (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal carcinoma undergoes PET-CT mainly to evaluate:",o:["Hearing loss severity","Tumor spread and distant metastasis","Vestibular function","Salivary flow","Thyroid hormone production"],a:1,e:"PET-CT identifies metabolically active regional and distant disease in advanced laryngeal cancer. Weight loss and nodal metastasis develop clinically in extensive tumors.<br><br>It is especially useful for staging recurrent or advanced disease.<br><br>Hearing assessment (option A), vestibular testing (option C), salivary flow (option D), and thyroid function (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal cancer develops aspiration after partial laryngectomy because the surgery compromises:",o:["Vestibular function","Nasal mucociliary clearance","Facial nerve integrity","Airway protective mechanisms","Eustachian tube opening"],a:3,e:"Partial laryngectomy may impair epiglottic closure and glottic competence. Aspiration develops clinically especially during early postoperative swallowing rehabilitation.<br><br>Speech and swallow therapy are essential after organ-preserving procedures.<br><br>Vestibular function (option A), facial nerve integrity (option C), mucociliary clearance (option B), and Eustachian tube function (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with early glottic carcinoma treated by radiotherapy develops persistent edema and recurrent hoarseness. The next important step is:",o:["Ignore symptoms because edema is always benign","Septoplasty","Immediate thyroidectomy","Repeat laryngoscopic evaluation and biopsy","Mastoidectomy"],a:3,e:"Persistent or recurrent hoarseness after treatment may indicate residual or recurrent malignancy. Vocal cord edema develops clinically after radiation but recurrence must always be excluded.<br><br>Histological reassessment is therefore essential.<br><br>Ignoring symptoms (option A), thyroidectomy (option C), septoplasty (option B), and mastoidectomy (option E) are inappropriate.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with verrucous carcinoma of larynx differs from conventional squamous carcinoma because verrucous carcinoma:",o:["Commonly metastasizes early","Never causes hoarseness","Originates from cartilage","Is well differentiated with locally invasive growth","Commonly produces distant metastasis"],a:3,e:"Verrucous carcinoma is a low-grade variant characterized by slow locally destructive behavior. Persistent hoarseness develops clinically because lesions involve vocal cords.<br><br>Nodal and distant metastases are relatively uncommon.<br><br>Early metastasis (option A), cartilaginous origin (option C), absence of hoarseness (option B), and common distant spread (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The strongest etiological factor for laryngeal carcinoma is:",o:["Chronic otitis media","Nasal polyposis","Allergic rhinitis","Cigarette smoking","Ménière disease"],a:3,e:"Tobacco exposure remains the principal risk factor for laryngeal malignancy. Persistent hoarseness develops clinically in smokers with glottic involvement.<br><br>Alcohol acts synergistically in increasing malignant risk.<br><br>Otitis media (option A), allergic rhinitis (option C), nasal polyposis (option B), and Ménière disease (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal carcinoma involving anterior commissure is concerning because tumors here:",o:["Cannot spread to cartilage","May invade thyroid cartilage early","Never metastasize","Cause bilateral deafness","Remain superficial permanently"],a:1,e:"The anterior commissure lies closely related to thyroid cartilage via Broyles ligament. Early cartilage invasion develops clinically with tumors involving this region.<br><br>This may worsen prognosis and influence treatment planning.<br><br>Absence of spread (option A), lack of metastasis (option C), deafness (option D), and permanent superficiality (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Recall and Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with total laryngectomy develops leakage of saliva through neck wound postoperatively. The most likely complication is:",o:["Chylous fistula","Pharyngocutaneous fistula","Tracheomalacia","Bell palsy","Vocal cord granuloma"],a:1,e:"Breakdown of pharyngeal closure after laryngectomy may create salivary fistula into neck wound. Fever and wound contamination develop clinically postoperatively.<br><br>Radiotherapy and malnutrition increase risk significantly.<br><br>Chylous fistula (option A), tracheomalacia (option C), Bell palsy (option D), and granuloma (option E) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after total laryngectomy undergoes tracheoesophageal puncture mainly to restore:",o:["Swallowing reflex","Hearing acuity","Nasal breathing","Speech function","Vestibular balance"],a:3,e:"Tracheoesophageal puncture allows pulmonary air to vibrate pharyngoesophageal segment for voice production. Aphonia develops clinically after total laryngectomy without rehabilitation.<br><br>Voice prostheses significantly improve communication quality.<br><br>Swallowing reflex (option A), nasal breathing (option C), hearing (option B), and balance (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced laryngeal carcinoma develops fixation of hemilarynx on examination. This finding suggests:",o:["Early superficial disease only","Deep infiltrative tumor spread","Benign vocal polyp","Acute viral laryngitis","Psychogenic aphonia"],a:1,e:"Hemilaryngeal fixation indicates invasion of intrinsic musculature or cricoarytenoid joint. Progressive airway symptoms and dysphagia develop clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>This finding carries significant staging implications.<br><br>Superficial disease (option A), vocal polyp (option C), viral laryngitis (option D), and psychogenic aphonia (option E) are less likely.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent glottic carcinoma after laser excision develops persistent airway narrowing. The most likely late complication is:",o:["Subglottic stenosis","Ménière disease","Otosclerosis","Facial paralysis","Vestibular neuritis"],a:0,e:"Repeated surgery and radiation may produce fibrosis within laryngeal airway. Progressive dyspnea and stridor develop clinically because of airway narrowing.<br><br>Airway reconstructive procedures may become necessary.<br><br>Ménière disease (option B), otosclerosis (option C), facial paralysis (option D), and vestibular neuritis (option E) are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with supraglottic carcinoma undergoes bilateral neck dissection because supraglottic lymphatic drainage is:",o:["Minimal and unilateral only","Confined to posterior triangle","Absent entirely","Rich and often bilateral","Independent of cervical nodes"],a:3,e:"Supraglottic lymphatics cross midline extensively, predisposing to bilateral nodal spread. Neck masses develop clinically early in supraglottic cancer.<br><br>This anatomical pattern influences surgical planning significantly.<br><br>Minimal unilateral drainage (option A), absent drainage (option C), isolated posterior triangle spread (option B), and independence from cervical nodes (option E) are incorrect.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal carcinoma develops severe dysphagia and aspiration. Which structure is most likely extensively involved?",o:["Subglottis only","Tracheal rings only","Cricoid cartilage only","Supraglottic larynx","Thyroid isthmus"],a:3,e:"The supraglottis plays a major role in airway protection during swallowing. Dysphagia and aspiration develop clinically when tumors involve epiglottis and aryepiglottic folds.<br><br>Advanced supraglottic lesions commonly impair swallowing significantly.<br><br>Subglottis (option A), isolated cricoid involvement (option C), tracheal rings (option B), and thyroid isthmus (option E) are less responsible.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal carcinoma and severe airway obstruction requires emergency tracheostomy because the tumor has produced:",o:["Extrathoracic upper airway narrowing","Pleural restriction","Pulmonary edema","Bronchiectasis","Alveolar collapse exclusively"],a:0,e:"Laryngeal tumors obstruct the upper airway causing turbulent inspiratory airflow and stridor. Progressive respiratory distress develops clinically in advanced disease.<br><br>Emergency airway establishment may become lifesaving.<br><br>Pleural restriction (option B), pulmonary edema (option C), bronchiectasis (option D), and isolated alveolar collapse (option E) are less relevant mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 64-year-old man develops sudden nonfluent speech after left middle cerebral artery infarction. He understands commands but speaks with great effort and short phrases. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Wernicke aphasia","Broca aphasia","Dysarthria","Dysphonia","Mutism"],a:1,e:"Broca aphasia results from dominant inferior frontal lobe injury affecting motor speech production. Patients develop clinically nonfluent effortful speech with relatively preserved comprehension.<br><br>Writing is often similarly impaired, and associated right-sided weakness may coexist because of adjacent motor cortex involvement. This differentiates it from Wernicke aphasia, where speech remains fluent but comprehension is markedly impaired.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient speaks fluently but produces meaningless sentences and cannot comprehend spoken language. The lesion most likely involves:",o:["Broca area","Cerebellum","Wernicke area","Basal ganglia","Hypoglossal nucleus"],a:2,e:"Wernicke aphasia occurs due to damage in the dominant posterior superior temporal region. Fluent but nonsensical speech develops clinically along with impaired comprehension and poor repetition.<br><br>Patients are often unaware of their deficits and may produce paraphasic errors or invented words. This differs from dysarthria, where language formulation is intact but articulation is impaired because of neuromuscular dysfunction.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Parkinson disease develops monotonous soft speech and reduced articulation. The speech disorder is best termed:",o:["Aphonia","Dysphagia","Aphasia","Dysarthria","Echolalia"],a:3,e:"Dysarthria is a motor speech disorder caused by impaired neuromuscular control of articulation. Parkinsonian speech develops clinically with hypophonia, monotony, and reduced facial expression.<br><br>Language comprehension and word selection remain preserved, helping distinguish dysarthria from aphasia. Management commonly involves speech therapy techniques focusing on breath support, articulation, and vocal intensity training.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after total laryngectomy communicates by trapping air in the esophagus and releasing it for phonation. This method is called:",o:["Tracheoesophageal speech","Esophageal speech","Electrolaryngeal resonance","Glossopharyngeal speech","Ventricular phonation"],a:1,e:"Esophageal speech utilizes swallowed air released through the pharyngoesophageal segment to create sound. Aphonia develops clinically after total laryngectomy because vocal cords are removed completely.<br><br>Although difficult to master, esophageal speech avoids dependence on external devices. Compared with tracheoesophageal puncture speech, however, it generally produces shorter phrase lengths and lower vocal intensity.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with normal intelligence has difficulty producing specific speech sounds despite intact comprehension and hearing. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Aphasia","Dysphonia","Articulation disorder","Stuttering","Mutism"],a:2,e:"Articulation disorders involve impaired production of speech sounds despite preserved language development. Mispronunciation develops clinically without deficits in comprehension or cognition.<br><br>Common examples include substitution, omission, or distortion of consonants. Hearing assessment remains important because chronic hearing impairment may worsen articulation development during early childhood.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis most commonly develops:",o:["Fluent aphasia","Dyslexia","Receptive aphasia","Dysphonia","Echolalia"],a:3,e:"Dysphonia refers to abnormal voice quality caused by laryngeal dysfunction. Vocal cord paralysis produces clinically breathy hoarseness because glottic closure becomes incomplete during phonation.<br><br>Patients may also complain of weak cough and aspiration. Flexible laryngoscopy is essential to evaluate cord mobility and identify the underlying etiology of nerve injury.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with cerebellar disease develops scanning speech characterized by irregular rhythm and variable intensity. This represents:",o:["Spastic dysarthria","Ataxic dysarthria","Flaccid dysarthria","Aphonia","Dysphasia"],a:1,e:"Ataxic dysarthria results from cerebellar dysfunction affecting coordination of speech musculature. Speech develops clinically with irregular rhythm, inappropriate pauses, and altered stress patterns.<br><br>Associated gait ataxia, intention tremor, and nystagmus commonly coexist. This differs from spastic dysarthria, where speech is strained and slow because of upper motor neuron involvement.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child develops repetition of syllables and speech blocks during conversation. The diagnosis is:",o:["Dysarthria","Dysphonia","Aphasia","Stuttering","Mutism"],a:3,e:"Stuttering is a fluency disorder characterized by repetition, prolongation, and involuntary speech interruption. Symptoms develop clinically during early childhood and may worsen with anxiety.<br><br>Speech therapy focusing on fluency-shaping techniques remains central to management. Most children improve substantially with early intervention and supportive communication strategies.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral vocal cord paralysis undergoes medialization thyroplasty primarily to improve:",o:["Articulation","Hearing thresholds","Language comprehension","Voice quality and glottic closure","Cognitive processing"],a:3,e:"Medialization thyroplasty repositions the paralyzed vocal cord toward the midline. Breathy dysphonia develops clinically because of persistent glottic insufficiency.<br><br>Improved glottic closure enhances vocal intensity and reduces aspiration risk during swallowing. Voice outcomes are generally better when performed after stabilization of nerve recovery potential.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after stroke understands spoken language but cannot repeat phrases despite fluent speech. The lesion most likely involves the:",o:["Arcuate fasciculus","Cerebellum","Hypoglossal nucleus","Facial nerve","Basal ganglia"],a:0,e:"Conduction aphasia results from disruption of the arcuate fasciculus connecting Broca and Wernicke areas. Fluent speech develops clinically with relatively preserved comprehension but markedly impaired repetition.<br><br>Patients frequently recognize their speech errors and attempt repeated self-correction, distinguishing this disorder from Wernicke aphasia where insight is often poor.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 58-year-old teacher presents with progressive vocal fatigue, hoarseness worsening by evening, and intermittent nasal speech. Examination reveals fatigable palatal weakness and fluctuating dysphonia. The most likely underlying disorder is:",o:["Myasthenia gravis","Broca aphasia","Vocal cord papilloma","Spasmodic dysphonia","Parkinson disease"],a:0,e:"Myasthenia gravis causes fatigable weakness of bulbar and laryngeal musculature. Nasal speech and fluctuating dysphonia develop clinically with worsening after prolonged voice use.<br><br>Associated ptosis or diplopia may provide additional diagnostic clues. Electromyography and acetylcholine receptor antibody testing are important investigations supporting diagnosis and management planning.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with spasmodic dysphonia most commonly demonstrates:",o:["Fluent aphasia","Complete aphonia continuously","Bilateral vocal cord fixation","Involuntary laryngeal muscle contractions during speech","Receptive language deficit"],a:3,e:"Spasmodic dysphonia is a focal laryngeal dystonia producing strained or interrupted voice quality. Speech develops clinically with involuntary spasms affecting phonation.<br><br>Botulinum toxin injection into affected laryngeal muscles remains the most effective symptomatic treatment and often requires repeated administration at regular intervals.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe hearing loss develops impaired speech articulation mainly because:",o:["Vocal cords become paralyzed","Cerebellar control fails","Broca area degenerates","Auditory feedback is reduced","Tongue mobility decreases"],a:3,e:"Normal speech development depends heavily on auditory feedback mechanisms. Articulation abnormalities develop clinically in profound hearing impairment, especially when onset occurs during childhood.<br><br>Early hearing rehabilitation with hearing aids or cochlear implantation significantly improves language acquisition and speech intelligibility outcomes.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bulbar palsy develops slurred nasal speech because of weakness involving:",o:["Upper motor neurons only","Cervical sympathetic chain","Vestibular pathways","Lower cranial nerves supplying speech muscles","Optic pathways"],a:3,e:"Bulbar palsy affects cranial nerves controlling articulation, phonation, and swallowing. Dysarthria develops clinically with nasal quality, weak cough, and aspiration tendency.<br><br>Tongue wasting and fasciculations may also be present, helping differentiate bulbar palsy from pseudobulbar palsy, where emotional lability predominates.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with total laryngectomy uses a handheld vibrating device against the neck to communicate. This device is called:",o:["Resonance amplifier","Electrolarynx","Palatal obturator","Nasometer","Pneumophone"],a:1,e:"An electrolarynx generates external vibrations transmitted through neck tissues to produce speech. Aphonia develops clinically after removal of the larynx and vocal cords.<br><br>Although speech may sound mechanical, the device allows rapid postoperative communication while patients learn more advanced rehabilitation techniques if desired.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with pseudobulbar palsy characteristically demonstrates:",o:["Emotional lability with spastic dysarthria","Fluent aphasia","Complete mutism","Isolated vocal cord paralysis","Pure receptive language loss"],a:0,e:"Pseudobulbar palsy results from bilateral upper motor neuron lesions affecting corticobulbar pathways. Slow strained speech develops clinically with exaggerated emotional responses such as pathological laughing or crying.<br><br>Jaw jerk reflex is typically brisk, contrasting with bulbar palsy where lower motor neuron signs predominate.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with delayed speech development should initially undergo assessment of:",o:["Thyroid gland only","Cervical spine mobility","Vestibular pathways","Hearing function","Facial sensation"],a:3,e:"Hearing impairment is a major reversible cause of delayed speech acquisition. Poor language development develops clinically when auditory input is insufficient during critical developmental years.<br><br>Audiological evaluation should therefore form a routine component of assessment in all children presenting with delayed speech milestones.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe dysarthria but intact writing and comprehension most likely has preserved:",o:["Motor speech articulation only","Hearing pathways only","Vocal cord mobility","Language formulation centers","Facial musculature"],a:3,e:"Dysarthria affects the motor execution of speech while language processing remains intact. Patients understand commands and communicate effectively through writing clinically despite impaired articulation.<br><br>This distinction is important because aphasia involves disruption of language formulation and comprehension rather than speech mechanics alone.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal carcinoma after radiotherapy develops persistent rough hoarseness. The definitive method to exclude recurrence is:",o:["Pure tone audiometry","Vestibular testing","Tympanometry","Laryngoscopic biopsy","Thyroid scan"],a:3,e:"Persistent dysphonia after radiotherapy may indicate recurrent malignancy despite post-radiation edema. Hoarseness develops clinically because recurrent tumors impair vocal cord vibration.<br><br>Histopathological confirmation remains essential before planning salvage surgery or further oncological treatment.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with expressive aphasia becomes frustrated because he:",o:["Cannot understand spoken language","Cannot move facial muscles","Has complete hearing loss","Knows intended words but cannot produce them fluently","Loses consciousness during speech"],a:3,e:"Expressive aphasia preserves comprehension while impairing verbal output. Patients develop clinically nonfluent speech with awareness of communication difficulty.<br><br>This preserved insight often causes emotional frustration and anxiety, unlike receptive aphasia where awareness of deficits may be limited.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy develops aspiration mainly because:",o:["Nasal cavity collapses","Incomplete glottic closure occurs during swallowing","Tongue loses all movement","Esophageal peristalsis stops","Palate becomes rigid"],a:1,e:"Glottic incompetence allows food or liquids to enter the airway during deglutition. Coughing during feeds develops clinically in significant unilateral vocal cord paralysis.<br><br>Speech and swallowing rehabilitation are important components of long-term management in affected patients.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with stuttering is most likely to worsen during:",o:["Relaxed solitary reading","Whispered speech","Singing activities","Emotional stress and anxiety","Automatic speech patterns"],a:3,e:"Psychological stress commonly exacerbates fluency disorders. Speech interruptions and syllable repetitions develop clinically more prominently during emotionally stressful social interactions.<br><br>Interestingly, many patients experience improved fluency during singing or rhythmic speech activities.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe laryngeal trauma loses normal phonation because sound production primarily depends upon:",o:["Nasal resonance only","Salivary secretion","Tongue mobility exclusively","Vocal cord vibration","Palatal rigidity"],a:3,e:"Normal voice production requires coordinated vibration of true vocal cords during expiration. Dysphonia develops clinically when trauma disrupts laryngeal structure or cord mobility.<br><br>Even subtle mucosal abnormalities may significantly impair vocal quality because vibration must remain symmetrical and regular.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with progressive dysarthria, tongue wasting, and fasciculations most likely has involvement of:",o:["Upper motor neuron pathways only","Visual cortex","Vestibular system","Lower motor neuron cranial nuclei","Cerebellar peduncles exclusively"],a:3,e:"Lower motor neuron degeneration affecting bulbar musculature produces flaccid dysarthria. Weak slurred speech develops clinically with tongue atrophy and fasciculations.<br><br>Motor neuron disease remains an important differential diagnosis in such presentations and requires neurological evaluation.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after total laryngectomy develops fluent communication using a tracheoesophageal prosthesis because the prosthesis allows:",o:["Direct vocal cord regeneration","Tongue-based phonation","Nasal resonance restoration only","Pulmonary air to vibrate pharyngoesophageal tissues","Automatic laryngeal closure"],a:3,e:"Tracheoesophageal puncture redirects expired pulmonary air into the pharyngoesophageal segment to generate sound. Voice rehabilitation develops clinically with more natural phrasing compared with esophageal speech.<br><br>The prosthesis requires regular maintenance because leakage or blockage may occur over time.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with cerebellar lesion demonstrates irregular explosive speech. Which associated neurological sign is most likely present?",o:["Bradykinesia","Hyperacusis","Facial paralysis","Intention tremor","Anosmia"],a:3,e:"Cerebellar dysfunction impairs coordination of both limb movement and speech articulation. Ataxic dysarthria develops clinically with scanning rhythm and variable stress.<br><br>Associated intention tremor and gait ataxia strongly support cerebellar involvement rather than cortical aphasic disorders.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with chronic smoking and persistent hoarseness undergoes flexible laryngoscopy showing unilateral irregular vocal cord lesion. The next best step is:",o:["Observation for one year","Direct laryngoscopy with biopsy","Speech therapy only","Vestibular testing","Nasal endoscopy exclusively"],a:1,e:"Suspicious unilateral vocal cord lesions require histopathological diagnosis. Persistent dysphonia develops clinically early in glottic malignancy because cord vibration becomes abnormal.<br><br>Delaying biopsy risks progression to advanced disease with poorer functional outcomes and survival rates.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with psychogenic aphonia usually retains the ability to:",o:["Produce voluntary speech normally","Swallow saliva","Understand no language","Move vocal cords minimally","Cough normally"],a:4,e:"Psychogenic aphonia often preserves involuntary vocalization despite inability to speak voluntarily. Normal cough sounds develop clinically because true vocal cords remain structurally intact.<br><br>Recognition of this finding helps distinguish functional disorders from organic vocal cord paralysis.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with Parkinson disease develops speech abnormalities mainly because of:",o:["Auditory cortex destruction","Tongue paralysis alone","Bilateral vocal cord fixation","Laryngeal carcinoma","Basal ganglia dysfunction affecting motor control"],a:4,e:"Basal ganglia dysfunction impairs initiation and modulation of motor activity including speech. Hypophonic monotonous speech develops clinically in Parkinson disease.<br><br>Associated bradykinesia, rigidity, and resting tremor commonly coexist and contribute to communication difficulty.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with speech disorder is unable to name familiar objects despite fluent speech and preserved repetition. The deficit is most consistent with:",o:["Broca aphasia","Global aphasia","Dysarthria","Dysphonia","Anomic aphasia"],a:4,e:"Anomic aphasia primarily impairs word retrieval while preserving fluency and comprehension. Patients develop clinically circumlocutory speech because specific names cannot be recalled.<br><br>This disorder may occur after focal cortical injury or during recovery from broader aphasic syndromes.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest indication for emergency tracheostomy in ENT practice is:",o:["Chronic otitis media","Septal deviation","Ménière disease","Allergic rhinitis","Upper airway obstruction"],a:4,e:"Tracheostomy is most frequently performed to bypass obstructed upper airway. Stridor and respiratory distress develop clinically in laryngeal trauma, malignancy, or severe infections.<br><br>The procedure provides a secure airway below the level of obstruction and may be lifesaving when endotracheal intubation becomes impossible or unsafe.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The preferred site for standard tracheostomy is usually between the:",o:["First and second tracheal rings","Thyroid cartilage and cricoid cartilage","Cricoid cartilage and first ring only","Fourth and fifth rings exclusively","Second and third tracheal rings"],a:4,e:"Standard tracheostomy is commonly created between the second and third tracheal rings to avoid subglottic injury. Respiratory compromise develops clinically in patients requiring prolonged airway access.<br><br>Higher tracheostomy increases risk of subglottic stenosis, whereas lower procedures risk injury to major mediastinal vessels.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most dangerous immediate complication during tracheostomy is:",o:["Tracheal stenosis","Hemorrhage and loss of airway","Tracheocutaneous fistula","Tube crusting","Dysphonia"],a:1,e:"Airway loss and major bleeding are critical intraoperative complications during tracheostomy. Cyanosis and hypoxia develop clinically within minutes if airway control fails.<br><br>Careful surgical exposure and maintenance of oxygenation remain essential throughout the procedure, particularly in anatomically difficult necks.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with prolonged endotracheal intubation is planned for tracheostomy mainly to:",o:["Improve hearing","Restore vocal cord mobility","Prevent sinusitis","Treat aspiration permanently","Reduce complications of prolonged intubation"],a:4,e:"Long-term endotracheal intubation predisposes to laryngeal edema, ulceration, and subglottic stenosis. Tracheostomy develops clinically as a safer long-term airway alternative in ventilated patients.<br><br>It also reduces dead space, facilitates pulmonary toilet, and improves patient comfort during prolonged respiratory support.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"In children, tracheostomy is technically more difficult primarily because the trachea is:",o:["Calcified and rigid","Fixed to vertebral bodies","Completely intrathoracic","Devoid of cartilage","Small, soft, and mobile"],a:4,e:"Pediatric tracheas are narrow, compressible, and highly mobile, increasing technical difficulty during surgery. Airway obstruction develops clinically more rapidly because pediatric airway diameter is naturally small.<br><br>Accidental posterior wall injury or false passage formation occurs more easily in children compared with adults.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 48-year-old patient with carcinoma larynx develops progressive inspiratory stridor and suprasternal retraction. Flexible laryngoscopy demonstrates near-complete glottic obstruction. The most appropriate immediate management is:",o:["Oral antibiotics only","Emergency tracheostomy","Voice therapy","Total thyroidectomy","Radiotherapy without airway intervention"],a:1,e:"Severe upper airway obstruction from laryngeal malignancy requires urgent airway establishment. Cyanosis and respiratory distress develop clinically because airflow through the glottis becomes critically narrowed.<br><br>Definitive oncological treatment should follow only after securing a stable airway and adequate oxygenation.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The structure commonly divided or retracted during tracheostomy is the:",o:["Facial artery","Thoracic duct","Internal carotid artery","Submandibular gland","Thyroid isthmus"],a:4,e:"The thyroid isthmus overlies upper tracheal rings and often requires division or superior retraction during surgery. Bleeding develops clinically if careful hemostasis is not achieved.<br><br>Knowledge of anterior neck anatomy is therefore essential for safe tracheostomy performance.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"Surgical emphysema after tracheostomy usually results from:",o:["Hyperthyroidism","Pulmonary fibrosis","Vocal cord paralysis","Facial nerve injury","Air leakage into cervical tissues"],a:4,e:"Improper tube positioning or tight wound closure may force air into fascial planes. Neck swelling and crepitus develop clinically around the tracheostomy site.<br><br>Correct tube placement and loose skin closure help reduce this complication significantly.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common late complication of tracheostomy is:",o:["Tracheal stenosis","Facial paralysis","Otitis media","Septal perforation","Glossitis"],a:0,e:"Pressure necrosis and healing fibrosis may narrow the tracheal lumen after prolonged tracheostomy. Progressive dyspnea develops clinically weeks or months after decannulation.<br><br>Excessive cuff pressure and high tracheostomy placement increase the likelihood of stenosis formation.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with tracheostomy suddenly develops respiratory distress due to tube blockage. The commonest cause is:",o:["Tracheomalacia","Mucus plugging","Pneumothorax","Carotid injury","Thyroid storm"],a:1,e:"Dry secretions and crust formation may obstruct the tracheostomy tube acutely. Sudden respiratory distress develops clinically with noisy breathing and reduced airflow.<br><br>Humidification and regular suctioning remain essential components of postoperative tracheostomy care.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The cuff of a tracheostomy tube primarily functions to:",o:["Improve speech quality","Reduce salivary secretion","Increase nasal airflow","Prevent vocal cord paralysis","Prevent air leak and aspiration"],a:4,e:"Inflated cuffs seal the tracheal lumen around the tube, improving ventilation efficiency. Aspiration risk develops clinically when airway protection is inadequate in ventilated patients.<br><br>Excessive cuff pressure, however, may produce tracheal mucosal ischemia and later stenosis.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops massive hemorrhage several days after tracheostomy. The most feared cause is erosion into the:",o:["External jugular vein","Innominate artery","Internal carotid artery","Subclavian vein","Thyroid artery only"],a:1,e:"Tracheo-innominate fistula is a rare but often fatal complication of low tracheostomy. Sentinel bleeding may develop clinically before catastrophic hemorrhage occurs.<br><br>Immediate overinflation of cuff and urgent surgical intervention are lifesaving emergency measures.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The ideal neck position during tracheostomy is:",o:["Extreme flexion","Neutral rigid fixation","Rotation to left side","Rotation to right side","Mild extension"],a:4,e:"Neck extension elevates and stabilizes the trachea, improving surgical exposure. Airway compromise develops clinically if positioning becomes excessive in cervical spine injury patients.<br><br>A shoulder roll is commonly used to optimize operative positioning during elective tracheostomy.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after tracheostomy develops pneumothorax because of:",o:["Pleural injury during surgery","Vocal cord paralysis","Facial nerve trauma","Tracheal calcification","Salivary fistula formation"],a:0,e:"Apical pleural damage may occur particularly in low tracheostomies or pediatric procedures. Respiratory distress and reduced breath sounds develop clinically after pleural breach.<br><br>Chest radiography is important when postoperative pneumothorax is suspected.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A speaking valve attached to tracheostomy tube allows speech because it:",o:["Directs expired air through vocal cords","Bypasses the larynx permanently","Immobilizes the vocal cords","Reduces salivary flow","Expands the tracheal lumen directly"],a:0,e:"Speaking valves permit inspiration through the tube while redirecting expiration upward across the vocal cords. Phonation develops clinically when laryngeal airflow is restored.<br><br>Patients require adequate airway patency above the tracheostomy for safe valve use.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 5-year-old child with recurrent respiratory papillomatosis develops worsening biphasic stridor and repeated cyanotic episodes despite multiple endoscopic debulking procedures. The child is planned for tracheostomy. Which factor is most important when considering tracheostomy in papillomatosis?",o:["It permanently cures HPV infection","It restores normal vocal cord mobility","It prevents all future surgeries","It eliminates aspiration risk completely","It may promote distal tracheobronchial spread of papillomas"],a:4,e:"Tracheostomy in papillomatosis is avoided when possible because papillomas may seed distally into tracheobronchial tree. Severe airway obstruction develops clinically in advanced disease requiring airway stabilization.<br><br>Despite this risk, tracheostomy remains lifesaving in critically obstructed patients when alternative airway measures fail.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with tracheostomy develops difficulty passing suction catheter. The first suspicion should be:",o:["Tube obstruction or displacement","Facial palsy","Ménière disease","Septal hematoma","Glossopharyngeal injury"],a:0,e:"Difficulty passing a suction catheter strongly suggests blocked or malpositioned tracheostomy tube. Respiratory distress develops clinically if airway obstruction progresses.<br><br>Immediate tube assessment and replacement may be necessary to prevent hypoxic deterioration.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Percutaneous tracheostomy is commonly performed in:",o:["Intensive care unit patients requiring prolonged ventilation","Patients with neck malignancy exclusively","Acute otitis media cases","Ménière disease patients","Septoplasty procedures"],a:0,e:"Percutaneous tracheostomy provides bedside airway access in critically ill ventilated patients. Prolonged intubation develops clinically with increased risk of laryngeal complications.<br><br>Bronchoscopic guidance is frequently used to improve procedural safety during insertion.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The major advantage of tracheostomy over prolonged oral intubation is:",o:["Elimination of infection risk","Removal of need for suctioning","Permanent speech preservation","Prevention of aspiration completely","Improved patient comfort and pulmonary toilet"],a:4,e:"Tracheostomy facilitates secretion clearance and reduces airway resistance during prolonged ventilation. Patient comfort develops clinically with easier nursing care and reduced sedation requirements.<br><br>It also decreases laryngeal injury risk associated with extended endotracheal intubation.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after tracheostomy develops inability to phonate despite normal vocal cord mobility. The main reason is:",o:["Absence of airflow through vocal cords","Tongue paralysis","Cerebellar dysfunction","Loss of auditory feedback","Facial nerve injury"],a:0,e:"Air entering directly through the tracheostomy bypasses normal laryngeal airflow required for phonation. Aphonia develops clinically unless speaking valves or finger occlusion redirect expired air upward.<br><br>Voice rehabilitation is therefore an important aspect of postoperative tracheostomy management.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with prolonged cuff inflation develops tracheal stenosis because excessive cuff pressure causes:",o:["Vocal cord edema only","Facial paralysis","Pleural rupture","Esophageal perforation","Tracheal mucosal ischemia and fibrosis"],a:4,e:"High cuff pressures compromise mucosal blood supply leading to necrosis and later scarring. Progressive dyspnea develops clinically after decannulation in severe stenosis.<br><br>Modern high-volume low-pressure cuffs significantly reduce this complication risk when monitored appropriately.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops tracheoesophageal fistula after prolonged tracheostomy. The most likely mechanism is:",o:["Congenital malformation only","Pressure necrosis of posterior tracheal wall","Viral infection","Carotid artery injury","Nasal obstruction"],a:1,e:"Excessive cuff pressure may erode through posterior tracheal wall into esophagus. Aspiration and gastric distension develop clinically in affected patients.<br><br>Prevention depends upon careful cuff pressure monitoring and minimizing prolonged high-pressure inflation.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The most appropriate emergency management of accidental decannulation in a fresh tracheostomy is:",o:["Immediate blind reinsertion forcefully","Observe without intervention","Close the stoma with sutures","Begin oral feeding","Secure airway urgently while maintaining stoma patency"],a:4,e:"Fresh tracheostomy tracts may close rapidly after accidental tube removal. Respiratory compromise develops clinically if airway access is lost completely.<br><br>Prompt airway stabilization with experienced assistance is therefore critical during early postoperative periods.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe maxillofacial trauma undergoes tracheostomy because oral intubation is:",o:["More comfortable long-term","Responsible for sinusitis only","Associated with hearing loss","Contraindicated in all trauma","Difficult or impossible safely"],a:4,e:"Extensive facial injuries may distort anatomy and obstruct oral airway access. Respiratory distress develops clinically due to bleeding, edema, and structural disruption.<br><br>Tracheostomy therefore provides a secure airway independent of upper facial anatomy.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with tracheostomy develops recurrent chest infections mainly because:",o:["Humidification of inspired air is bypassed","Vocal cords become hypermobile","Auditory reflexes are impaired","Thyroid function decreases","Cerebellar coordination fails"],a:0,e:"Normal nasal airway warms and humidifies inspired air before reaching lower respiratory tract. Thick secretions develop clinically after tracheostomy because this function is bypassed.<br><br>Humidification systems and adequate suction care help reduce pulmonary complications significantly.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 72-year-old ventilated ICU patient with prolonged intubation undergoes percutaneous tracheostomy under bronchoscopic guidance. During the procedure, sudden oxygen desaturation and swelling of the neck occur. Which complication is most likely?",o:["Tracheal false passage with surgical emphysema","Ménière disease","Facial nerve paralysis","Otitis media","Thyroid storm"],a:0,e:"False passage formation allows air leakage into cervical tissues producing subcutaneous emphysema. Respiratory compromise develops clinically with sudden oxygen desaturation and neck swelling.<br><br>Bronchoscopic visualization helps minimize this complication by confirming intratracheal placement during the procedure.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The tube commonly preferred for long-term tracheostomy because of flexibility and reduced tissue irritation is:",o:["Silver tube exclusively","Glass tube","Steel cannula only","Wooden cannula","PVC or silicone tube"],a:4,e:"Modern synthetic tracheostomy tubes are flexible and less traumatic to tracheal mucosa. Long-term airway support develops clinically with improved patient comfort and easier care.<br><br>Metal tubes are more durable but less suitable for prolonged intensive care ventilation.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after tracheostomy develops persistent opening after decannulation. The condition is called:",o:["Tracheocutaneous fistula","Bronchopleural fistula","Pharyngocutaneous fistula","Laryngocele","Zenker diverticulum"],a:0,e:"Persistent epithelialized communication may remain after prolonged tracheostomy dependence. Air leakage develops clinically through the neck opening during coughing or speech.<br><br>Surgical closure may become necessary when spontaneous healing fails.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with airway obstruction from bilateral vocal cord paralysis undergoes tracheostomy because the cords typically remain in:",o:["Fully abducted position","Vertical orientation","Extreme lateral position","Oscillating motion","Paramedian position"],a:4,e:"Bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy leaves cords near the midline causing critical airway narrowing. Inspiratory stridor develops clinically despite relatively preserved phonation.<br><br>Tracheostomy bypasses the obstructed glottic airway and stabilizes respiration effectively.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The major physiological disadvantage of tracheostomy compared with normal nasal breathing is loss of:",o:["Vocal cord vibration only","Cardiac output regulation","Pulmonary gas exchange","Diaphragmatic movement","Filtration, humidification, and warming of inspired air"],a:4,e:"The upper airway normally conditions inspired air before it enters the lungs. Thick secretions and crusting develop clinically after tracheostomy because these protective mechanisms are bypassed.<br><br>Humidified oxygen and meticulous airway care are therefore essential during postoperative management.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 54-year-old smoker presents with progressive hoarseness for 6 months associated with mild dysphagia and weight loss. Flexible laryngoscopy shows an ulcerative lesion involving the right true vocal cord with impaired mobility. Which finding most strongly suggests advanced local invasion?",o:["Persistent hoarseness","Impaired vocal cord mobility","Mild odynophagia","Smoking history","Weight loss alone"],a:1,e:"Fixation or reduced mobility of a vocal cord strongly suggests infiltration of intrinsic laryngeal muscles or involvement of the cricoarytenoid joint. Hoarseness commonly develops early because glottic tumors interfere with mucosal vibration.<br><br>This finding upgrades tumor staging and usually indicates deeper disease extension. Such patients often require more aggressive management strategies including combined surgery and oncologic therapy.<br><br>Persistent hoarseness (A), odynophagia (C), smoking history (D), and weight loss (E) are important clinically but are less specific indicators of advanced local invasion.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The narrowest portion of the pediatric airway is traditionally considered the:",o:["Supraglottis","Glottis","Subglottis","Oropharynx","Nasopharynx"],a:2,e:"The pediatric subglottis, encircled by the cricoid cartilage, is anatomically the narrowest airway segment. Even minimal edema in this region may significantly reduce airway diameter and increase resistance.<br><br>This explains why conditions such as croup or congenital subglottic stenosis produce marked respiratory distress in infants and young children. Biphasic stridor is a common associated clinical feature.<br><br>Supraglottis (A), glottis (B), oropharynx (D), and nasopharynx (E) are not the narrowest pediatric airway regions.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis most critically develops:",o:["Complete aphasia","Inspiratory stridor","Conductive deafness","Hypernasality","Facial asymmetry"],a:1,e:"Bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis leaves the vocal cords near the paramedian position. The glottic airway therefore becomes critically narrowed during inspiration.<br><br>Patients may present with severe respiratory distress and cyanosis despite relatively preserved voice quality. Airway stabilization and tracheostomy may become urgently necessary in advanced obstruction.<br><br>Aphasia (A), conductive deafness (C), hypernasality (D), and facial asymmetry (E) are unrelated to bilateral vocal cord paralysis.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The sensory supply above the vocal cords is carried mainly by the:",o:["Recurrent laryngeal nerve","External laryngeal nerve","Internal laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Facial nerve"],a:2,e:"The internal laryngeal nerve supplies sensation above the true vocal cords including supraglottic mucosa. It is responsible for initiating the protective cough reflex.<br><br>Loss of this sensory supply predisposes patients to silent aspiration because laryngeal protective mechanisms become impaired during swallowing. This is clinically important in neurological and surgical injuries.<br><br>The recurrent laryngeal nerve (A) mainly supplies motor innervation below the cords, while the remaining options are unrelated.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A child develops inspiratory stridor worsening during feeding and crying but improving in prone position. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Bilateral choanal atresia","Laryngomalacia","Vocal cord papilloma","Acute epiglottitis","Retropharyngeal abscess"],a:1,e:"Laryngomalacia is the commonest congenital laryngeal anomaly and results from collapse of supraglottic structures during inspiration. Symptoms usually begin during early infancy.<br><br>Stridor typically worsens during feeding, crying, or supine positioning because inspiratory negative pressure increases supraglottic collapse. Most children improve spontaneously with maturation of laryngeal cartilages.<br><br>Choanal atresia (A), papilloma (C), epiglottitis (D), and retropharyngeal abscess (E) have different clinical presentations and airway findings.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 32-year-old motorcyclist presents after blunt anterior neck trauma with hoarseness, painful swallowing, surgical emphysema, and mild stridor. CT scan demonstrates thyroid cartilage fracture with mucosal tear. What is the most appropriate next step?",o:["Observation alone without airway monitoring","Immediate decannulation","Airway stabilization and surgical evaluation","Voice therapy only","Oral antihistamines"],a:2,e:"Laryngeal fractures with mucosal tears are potentially life-threatening injuries because edema and hematoma may rapidly worsen airway obstruction. Surgical emphysema strongly suggests airway disruption.<br><br>Securing the airway is always the first management priority before definitive imaging or reconstruction. Delayed respiratory deterioration may occur even when the patient initially appears stable.<br><br>Observation alone (A), decannulation (B), voice therapy (D), and antihistamines (E) are inappropriate in significant laryngeal trauma.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The only complete cartilaginous ring of the airway is the:",o:["Thyroid cartilage","Arytenoid cartilage","Epiglottis","Cricoid cartilage","Corniculate cartilage"],a:3,e:"The cricoid cartilage forms the only complete ring surrounding the airway. It provides structural support to the subglottic region and maintains airway patency.<br><br>Because the pediatric subglottis is naturally narrow, edema at the cricoid level can produce severe airway compromise rapidly. This anatomical relationship is clinically important in pediatric ENT emergencies.<br><br>The thyroid cartilage (A) is incomplete posteriorly, while the remaining cartilages do not form complete airway rings.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after thyroidectomy develops weak breathy voice and aspiration. Flexible laryngoscopy shows unilateral vocal cord immobility. The injured nerve is most likely the:",o:["External laryngeal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Facial nerve","Lingual nerve"],a:1,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve supplies all intrinsic laryngeal muscles except cricothyroid. Injury produces unilateral vocal cord paralysis with incomplete glottic closure.<br><br>Patients develop breathy dysphonia, weak cough, and sometimes aspiration during swallowing. Thyroid surgery remains one of the commonest causes of recurrent laryngeal nerve injury.<br><br>External laryngeal nerve injury (A) mainly affects pitch control, while the remaining options are unrelated to vocal cord mobility.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest symptom of early glottic carcinoma is:",o:["Neck swelling","Facial pain","Severe dysphagia","Hematemesis","Persistent hoarseness"],a:4,e:"Even small lesions involving the true vocal cords interfere with vibration and phonation. Persistent hoarseness therefore develops very early in glottic carcinoma.<br><br>Early symptom development contributes to relatively favorable prognosis because many glottic tumors are diagnosed before nodal metastasis or cartilage invasion occurs.<br><br>Neck swelling (A), severe dysphagia (C), hematemesis (D), and facial pain (E) usually occur later or are less characteristic.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe upper airway obstruction undergoes emergency tracheostomy. The preferred tracheal opening is usually made between the:",o:["First and second rings","Thyroid cartilage and cricoid cartilage","Fourth and fifth rings only","Cricoid cartilage and first ring","Second and third rings"],a:4,e:"Standard tracheostomy is commonly performed between the second and third tracheal rings. This level provides safe access while minimizing risk of subglottic injury.<br><br>Very high tracheostomies increase the likelihood of subglottic stenosis, whereas low tracheostomies may endanger major mediastinal vessels including the innominate artery.<br><br>The remaining options either risk important complications or are anatomically incorrect tracheostomy sites.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 67-year-old smoker presents with hoarseness, progressive dysphagia, referred otalgia, and left-sided cervical lymphadenopathy. Laryngoscopy reveals supraglottic ulcerative carcinoma involving epiglottis and aryepiglottic fold. Which anatomical characteristic explains the early nodal spread?",o:["Sparse supraglottic lymphatics","Rich bilateral lymphatic drainage","Absence of vascular supply","Bilateral recurrent nerve innervation","Poor mucosal permeability"],a:1,e:"The supraglottic larynx possesses abundant bilateral lymphatic drainage. Tumors arising in this region therefore metastasize to cervical lymph nodes relatively early.<br><br>Patients often present with neck masses, dysphagia, and referred otalgia before severe hoarseness develops. Bilateral nodal disease is also more common than in glottic cancers.<br><br>Sparse lymphatics (A), absent vascularity (C), recurrent nerve supply (D), and mucosal permeability (E) do not explain early nodal metastasis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with cerebellar lesion develops scanning speech characterized by irregular rhythm and explosive syllables. This speech disorder is classified as:",o:["Spastic dysarthria","Flaccid dysarthria","Ataxic dysarthria","Aphonia","Receptive aphasia"],a:2,e:"Ataxic dysarthria results from cerebellar dysfunction affecting coordination of speech musculature. Speech becomes irregular with variable stress and inappropriate pauses.<br><br>Associated cerebellar signs such as gait ataxia, intention tremor, and nystagmus frequently coexist and help localize the lesion clinically.<br><br>Spastic dysarthria (A) is associated with upper motor neuron lesions, while aphonia (D) and receptive aphasia (E) involve different mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The principal muscle responsible for vocal cord abduction is the:",o:["Cricothyroid muscle","Interarytenoid muscle","Thyroarytenoid muscle","Lateral cricoarytenoid muscle","Posterior cricoarytenoid muscle"],a:4,e:"The posterior cricoarytenoid muscles are the only abductors of the vocal cords and therefore play a critical role in maintaining airway patency during inspiration. Bilateral paralysis can produce severe airway obstruction.<br><br>Patients with bilateral posterior cricoarytenoid dysfunction often present with inspiratory stridor and respiratory distress because the vocal cords remain near the midline. Tracheostomy may become necessary in advanced obstruction.<br><br>The cricothyroid (A) controls pitch, while the remaining muscles mainly contribute to adduction and phonation rather than abduction.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with prolonged endotracheal intubation develops persistent hoarseness and posterior vocal cord granuloma. The most likely mechanism is:",o:["Viral infection","Allergic edema","Congenital malformation","Thyroid dysfunction","Pressure-related mucosal trauma"],a:4,e:"Intubation granulomas usually arise from pressure injury over the vocal process of arytenoid cartilages. Mucosal ulceration and chronic irritation interfere with normal vocal cord movement.<br><br>Patients commonly complain of persistent hoarseness, throat discomfort, and vocal fatigue after prolonged intubation. Gastroesophageal reflux and chronic throat clearing may further worsen or perpetuate these lesions.<br><br>Congenital malformations (C), thyroid dysfunction (D), and allergic edema (E) are not typical causes of posterior intubation granulomas.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with recurrent respiratory papillomatosis most commonly acquires the infection through:",o:["Hematogenous spread","Vertical maternal HPV transmission","Airborne fungal spores","Epstein-Barr virus infection","Tuberculous inoculation"],a:1,e:"Juvenile recurrent respiratory papillomatosis is associated mainly with HPV types 6 and 11 transmitted during childbirth. Papillomas repeatedly involve the vocal cords and laryngeal mucosa.<br><br>Children often present with progressive hoarseness, weak cry, and airway obstruction requiring repeated microlaryngoscopic debulking procedures over many years. Distal airway spread may occasionally occur in severe disease.<br><br>Hematogenous spread (A), fungal spores (C), Epstein-Barr virus (D), and tuberculosis (E) are not usual etiological mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Recall and Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 70-year-old man with transglottic carcinoma develops severe inspiratory stridor and cyanosis while awaiting surgery. Flexible laryngoscopy shows near-total airway obstruction. Which immediate intervention is most appropriate?",o:["Emergency radiotherapy only","Urgent tracheostomy","Oral corticosteroids alone","Voice rest","Nasogastric feeding only"],a:1,e:"Advanced laryngeal tumors may critically obstruct the airway and produce life-threatening respiratory compromise. Severe inspiratory stridor and cyanosis indicate impending airway failure.<br><br>Securing the airway always takes priority before definitive oncologic treatment. Tracheostomy bypasses the obstructed glottic airway and rapidly restores adequate ventilation and oxygenation.<br><br>Radiotherapy alone (A), corticosteroids (C), voice rest (D), and feeding measures (E) do not immediately relieve critical airway obstruction.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after total laryngectomy is unable to produce normal speech because the surgery removes the:",o:["Tongue base","Nasopharynx","Soft palate","Hypoglossal nerve","Vocal cords"],a:4,e:"Total laryngectomy removes the larynx including the true vocal cords responsible for normal phonation. Natural voice production therefore becomes impossible after surgery.<br><br>Speech rehabilitation remains an important component of postoperative care. Tracheoesophageal puncture, esophageal speech, and electrolarynx devices may help restore functional communication.<br><br>The tongue base (A), soft palate (C), hypoglossal nerve (D), and nasopharynx (E) are usually preserved during standard total laryngectomy.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral vocal cord paralysis most commonly presents with:",o:["Severe stridor only","Facial weakness","Complete aphasia","Bilateral deafness","Breathy hoarseness"],a:4,e:"Unilateral vocal cord paralysis causes incomplete glottic closure during phonation, allowing excessive air escape across the cords. This produces a weak breathy voice quality.<br><br>Patients may additionally complain of vocal fatigue, ineffective cough, and occasional aspiration during swallowing. Flexible laryngoscopy is essential for confirming vocal cord immobility.<br><br>Severe stridor (A) is more typical of bilateral paralysis, while the remaining options are neurologically unrelated.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The external laryngeal nerve supplies the:",o:["Posterior cricoarytenoid muscle","Lateral cricoarytenoid muscle","Thyroarytenoid muscle","Interarytenoid muscle","Cricothyroid muscle"],a:4,e:"The cricothyroid muscle tenses and elongates the vocal cords, helping regulate pitch during phonation. It is supplied by the external branch of the superior laryngeal nerve.<br><br>Injury to this nerve commonly produces vocal fatigue and inability to generate high-pitched sounds, particularly affecting singers and professional voice users.<br><br>The remaining intrinsic laryngeal muscles are supplied predominantly by the recurrent laryngeal nerve rather than the external laryngeal nerve.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with psychogenic aphonia is most likely to retain:",o:["Voluntary speech completely","Receptive aphasia","Bilateral vocal cord paralysis","Severe dysphagia","Normal cough sound"],a:4,e:"Psychogenic aphonia is a functional speech disorder in which voluntary phonation becomes impaired despite structurally normal vocal cords. Patients often speak only in whispers.<br><br>Involuntary vocalization such as coughing usually remains normal because the laryngeal musculature and neural pathways are intact. This finding helps distinguish psychogenic aphonia from organic vocal cord paralysis.<br><br>Bilateral paralysis (C), severe dysphagia (D), and receptive aphasia (E) are not characteristic features of psychogenic aphonia.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 4-year-old child presents with weak cry, recurrent aspiration during feeding, and recurrent chest infections. Flexible laryngoscopy demonstrates unilateral congenital vocal cord paralysis. Which mechanism most directly explains recurrent aspiration?",o:["Impaired auditory feedback","Cerebellar dysfunction","Reduced salivary secretion","Nasal cavity obstruction","Incomplete glottic closure during swallowing"],a:4,e:"Vocal cord immobility compromises airway protection during swallowing because the glottis cannot close effectively. Food and liquids may therefore enter the airway during feeds.<br><br>Children commonly present with coughing during feeding, recurrent aspiration pneumonia, and failure to thrive. Swallow assessment and airway monitoring are important parts of management.<br><br>Auditory feedback (A), salivary secretion (C), nasal obstruction (D), and cerebellar dysfunction (E) do not directly explain aspiration in unilateral vocal cord paralysis.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The investigation most essential for evaluating persistent unexplained hoarseness is:",o:["Tympanometry","Flexible laryngoscopy","Vestibular testing","CT brain","Sialography"],a:1,e:"Flexible laryngoscopy permits direct visualization of vocal cords, supraglottic structures, and laryngeal mucosa. Persistent hoarseness requires exclusion of structural lesions including malignancy.<br><br>It allows assessment of vocal cord mobility, mucosal irregularities, airway narrowing, and dynamic phonatory abnormalities in the outpatient setting with minimal discomfort.<br><br>Tympanometry (A), vestibular testing (C), CT brain (D), and sialography (E) are not primary investigations for chronic dysphonia.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with blunt laryngeal trauma develops surgical emphysema because of:",o:["Pulmonary fibrosis","Vocal nodules","Hyperthyroidism","Esophageal varices","Air leakage through mucosal tear"],a:4,e:"Laryngeal trauma may disrupt mucosa and cartilaginous framework, allowing air to escape into surrounding cervical fascial planes. Surgical emphysema presents clinically with neck swelling and palpable crepitus.<br><br>Associated hoarseness, stridor, hemoptysis, and dysphagia should raise suspicion of significant airway injury. CT imaging and flexible laryngoscopy are commonly required for complete assessment.<br><br>Pulmonary fibrosis (A), hyperthyroidism (C), esophageal varices (D), and vocal nodules (E) do not produce cervical surgical emphysema after neck trauma.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after tracheostomy suddenly develops severe respiratory distress. The first possibility to exclude is:",o:["Ménière disease","Glossitis","Acute otitis media","Facial palsy","Tube blockage or displacement"],a:4,e:"Tracheostomy obstruction from mucus plugging or tube displacement is a common life-threatening emergency. Airflow reduction rapidly produces cyanosis, agitation, and respiratory distress.<br><br>Immediate suctioning, inspection of tube patency, and airway stabilization are critical initial management steps. Delay in recognition may rapidly result in hypoxic collapse.<br><br>Ménière disease (A), otitis media (C), facial palsy (D), and glossitis (E) are unrelated to acute tracheostomy emergencies.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal carcinoma develops referred ear pain mainly through shared sensory innervation involving the:",o:["Facial nerve only","Accessory nerve exclusively","Hypoglossal nerve","Optic nerve","Glossopharyngeal and vagal pathways"],a:4,e:"The larynx and external auditory canal share sensory pathways through glossopharyngeal and vagal innervation. Referred otalgia is therefore a recognized symptom of laryngeal malignancy.<br><br>Persistent unilateral ear pain in smokers without obvious otologic pathology should prompt careful examination of the upper aerodigestive tract for occult malignancy.<br><br>Hypoglossal (C), optic (D), and accessory nerves (E) are not responsible for referred otalgia from laryngeal lesions.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 63-year-old smoker presents with persistent hoarseness and leukoplakic lesion over one vocal cord. Histology reveals severe dysplasia without invasion. Which statement is most accurate?",o:["The lesion has no malignant potential","Vocal cord mobility becomes irrelevant","Total laryngectomy is immediately mandatory","Radiotherapy is contraindicated permanently","It is a premalignant condition requiring close management"],a:4,e:"Severe epithelial dysplasia of the vocal cord carries substantial malignant transformation risk. Persistent dysphonia commonly develops because abnormal epithelium interferes with mucosal vibration.<br><br>Smoking cessation, regular surveillance, and definitive treatment of suspicious lesions are essential to prevent progression toward invasive squamous cell carcinoma.<br><br>Leukoplakia is not harmless (A), and total laryngectomy (C) is not routinely indicated in noninvasive dysplasia.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The posterior cricoarytenoid muscles receive motor supply from the:",o:["Internal laryngeal nerve","External laryngeal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve"],a:4,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve supplies all intrinsic laryngeal muscles except cricothyroid. Posterior cricoarytenoid muscles are especially important because they abduct the vocal cords.<br><br>Bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis may therefore produce severe airway compromise with inspiratory stridor due to inability of the cords to abduct.<br><br>The internal laryngeal nerve (A) is mainly sensory, while the remaining nerves do not control posterior cricoarytenoid function.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe laryngomalacia develops cyanotic episodes and failure to thrive. The preferred surgical treatment is:",o:["Thyroidectomy","Supraglottoplasty","Radical neck dissection","Septoplasty","Tonsillectomy only"],a:1,e:"Most cases of laryngomalacia improve spontaneously, but severe disease causing cyanosis or feeding difficulty may require surgery. Supraglottoplasty removes redundant supraglottic tissue causing inspiratory collapse.<br><br>The procedure improves airway patency and reduces feeding-related respiratory compromise while preserving normal laryngeal function in the majority of patients.<br><br>Thyroidectomy (A), radical neck dissection (C), septoplasty (D), and tonsillectomy (E) are unrelated procedures.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis undergoes medialization thyroplasty primarily to improve:",o:["Hearing acuity","Tongue mobility","Nasal resonance","Vestibular function","Glottic competence during phonation"],a:4,e:"Medialization thyroplasty repositions the paralyzed vocal cord toward the midline, reducing excessive air escape during speech. Patients therefore experience improved vocal intensity and clarity.<br><br>The procedure may additionally reduce aspiration by improving airway protection during swallowing. Voice outcomes are generally favorable in properly selected patients.<br><br>Hearing (A), vestibular function (D), and tongue mobility (E) are unaffected by medialization procedures.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced laryngeal carcinoma develops fixation of the hemilarynx on examination. This finding usually indicates:",o:["Early superficial lesion only","Functional dysphonia","Viral laryngitis","Vocal abuse syndrome","Deep infiltrative tumor spread"],a:4,e:"Hemilaryngeal fixation suggests infiltration of intrinsic laryngeal muscles or cricoarytenoid joint involvement by tumor. This usually indicates advanced disease.<br><br>Patients commonly present with worsening hoarseness, airway symptoms, dysphagia, and neck metastases once fixation develops. Staging and management become significantly affected by this finding.<br><br>Superficial lesions (A), viral laryngitis (C), vocal abuse (D), and functional dysphonia (E) do not typically produce hemilaryngeal fixation.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral vocal cord paralysis but relatively preserved voice most likely has cords lying in the:",o:["Fully abducted position","Oscillating position","Extreme lateral position","Vertical position","Paramedian position"],a:4,e:"Bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis commonly leaves the cords near the paramedian position. Phonation may remain relatively preserved because cords are near midline.<br><br>However, airway compromise becomes severe because the cords cannot abduct adequately during inspiration. Patients often present with stridor and respiratory distress despite acceptable voice quality.<br><br>Fully abducted cords (A) would produce breathy voice rather than airway obstruction. The remaining options are anatomically incorrect.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with supraglottic carcinoma is more likely than glottic carcinoma to present with:",o:["Early isolated hoarseness","Severe vertigo","Conductive hearing loss","Bilateral facial paralysis","Cervical lymph node metastasis"],a:4,e:"The supraglottis has abundant lymphatic drainage, allowing early spread to cervical lymph nodes. Patients often present with neck masses before marked voice symptoms occur.<br><br>Dysphagia, odynophagia, referred otalgia, and weight loss are additional common features of supraglottic tumors because of their anatomical location.<br><br>Glottic tumors more commonly present initially with isolated hoarseness rather than nodal metastasis.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with recurrent barking cough, inspiratory stridor, and subglottic narrowing on radiograph. The most likely diagnosis is:",o:["Acute epiglottitis","Croup","Vocal cord papilloma","Peritonsillar abscess","Retropharyngeal abscess"],a:1,e:"Croup is a viral laryngotracheobronchitis producing subglottic edema and airway narrowing. Inspiratory stridor and barking cough are characteristic clinical features.<br><br>Radiographs may show the classic \"steeple sign\" caused by narrowing of the subglottic airway. Most cases improve with corticosteroids and humidified oxygen therapy.<br><br>Epiglottitis (A) usually presents with toxic appearance and drooling, unlike typical viral croup.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent respiratory papillomatosis develops progressive airway obstruction despite repeated excisions. Which factor contributes to recurrence?",o:["HPV persistence within mucosa","Complete lack of vascularity","Auditory dysfunction","Tracheal calcification","Absence of epithelial involvement"],a:0,e:"Respiratory papillomatosis is caused by persistent HPV infection involving respiratory epithelium. Even after surgical excision, residual infected mucosa may generate recurrent papillomas.<br><br>Repeated procedures are therefore frequently necessary, particularly in aggressive childhood disease with extensive laryngeal involvement. Distal airway spread may occur in severe cases.<br><br>Auditory dysfunction (C) and tracheal calcification (D) do not explain recurrence patterns.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after prolonged tracheostomy develops progressive dyspnea weeks after decannulation. The most likely complication is:",o:["Vocal cord granuloma","Tracheal stenosis","Acute epiglottitis","Facial nerve palsy","Otosclerosis"],a:1,e:"Pressure injury from tracheostomy tubes or cuffs may cause fibrosis and narrowing of the tracheal lumen. Symptoms often appear gradually after decannulation.<br><br>Patients typically present with exertional dyspnea, stridor, and reduced airflow. Bronchoscopy and imaging are important for confirming the site and severity of stenosis.<br><br>Granuloma (A) and epiglottitis (C) usually present differently and are less likely after decannulation.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with muscle tension dysphonia most commonly demonstrates:",o:["Structural vocal cord destruction","Complete aphasia","Bilateral vocal cord paralysis","Glottic carcinoma","Excessive laryngeal muscular activity without structural lesion"],a:4,e:"Muscle tension dysphonia results from abnormal hyperfunctional use of laryngeal musculature during phonation. Patients complain of vocal fatigue, throat tightness, and strained voice quality.<br><br>Laryngoscopy usually demonstrates structurally normal vocal cords despite significant dysphonia. Voice therapy remains the primary management approach in most cases.<br><br>Carcinoma (D), aphasia (E), and vocal cord paralysis (C) involve different pathophysiological mechanisms.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 59-year-old smoker presents with persistent hoarseness, dysphagia, and aspiration during swallowing. Flexible laryngoscopy reveals a large supraglottic mass involving the epiglottis. Which physiological function of the supraglottis is most impaired in this patient?",o:["Olfaction","Airway protection during swallowing","Sound conduction","Salivary secretion","Auditory localization"],a:1,e:"The supraglottic larynx plays a critical role in preventing aspiration during deglutition. Tumors involving the epiglottis and aryepiglottic folds impair laryngeal closure mechanisms.<br><br>Patients commonly develop coughing during meals, aspiration pneumonia, and dysphagia. Supraglottic lesions therefore often present with swallowing difficulty earlier than glottic tumors.<br><br>Olfaction (A), sound conduction (C), salivation (D), and auditory localization (E) are unrelated supraglottic functions.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The lymphatic drainage of the true vocal cords is characteristically:",o:["Rich and bilateral","Connected directly to thoracic duct only","Directed exclusively to posterior triangle nodes","Absent below the glottis","Sparse or minimal"],a:4,e:"The true vocal cords contain relatively sparse lymphatic channels compared with the supraglottic larynx. This anatomical feature delays nodal metastasis in early glottic carcinoma.<br><br>Patients therefore often present with isolated hoarseness before cervical lymphadenopathy develops. This contributes significantly to the favorable prognosis of early glottic cancer.<br><br>Rich bilateral drainage (A) is more characteristic of the supraglottic region rather than the true vocal cords.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal trauma develops worsening stridor after initially appearing stable. The most likely mechanism is:",o:["Delayed edema and hematoma formation","Immediate vocal cord regeneration","Acute salivary hypersecretion","Sudden tracheal calcification","Middle ear infection"],a:0,e:"Laryngeal trauma may initially appear mild before progressive edema and hematoma formation worsen airway narrowing. Delayed respiratory compromise is therefore a recognized danger.<br><br>Patients require careful airway observation even when early symptoms seem limited. Progressive stridor, hoarseness, or crepitus should prompt urgent reassessment.<br><br>Vocal cord regeneration (B), salivary hypersecretion (C), and tracheal calcification (D) do not explain delayed airway deterioration.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The primary function of the cricothyroid muscle is to:",o:["Abduct vocal cords","Adduct vocal cords","Tense and elongate vocal cords","Relax aryepiglottic folds","Depress epiglottis"],a:2,e:"The cricothyroid muscle increases vocal cord tension and length, thereby raising pitch during phonation. It is innervated by the external branch of the superior laryngeal nerve.<br><br>Injury to this nerve commonly causes difficulty producing high-pitched sounds and vocal fatigue, especially in singers and professional voice users.<br><br>Posterior cricoarytenoid muscles mainly abduct cords, while lateral cricoarytenoid muscles contribute to adduction.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A child presents with weak cry and biphasic stridor since birth. Endoscopy demonstrates a thin membrane between the vocal cords. The diagnosis is:",o:["Laryngeal papillomatosis","Vocal cord polyp","Congenital laryngeal web","Subglottic hemangioma","Acute laryngitis"],a:2,e:"Congenital laryngeal webs result from incomplete recanalization of the embryonic larynx. The lesion partially obstructs the glottic airway and interferes with normal phonation.<br><br>Affected infants commonly present with weak cry, stridor, and respiratory distress of varying severity depending on the extent of obstruction.<br><br>Papillomatosis (A) and vocal polyps (B) usually present later and have different endoscopic appearances.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 46-year-old teacher complains of chronic hoarseness worsening after prolonged speaking. Laryngoscopy shows bilateral symmetrical swellings at the junction of anterior one-third and posterior two-thirds of the cords. What is the most likely diagnosis?",o:["Vocal nodules","Glottic carcinoma","Intubation granuloma","Laryngeal papilloma","Reinke edema"],a:0,e:"Vocal nodules commonly develop due to chronic phonotrauma in professional voice users. They typically arise at the point of maximal vibratory stress on the cords.<br><br>Patients present with progressive hoarseness, vocal fatigue, and reduced voice quality. Voice therapy and correction of abusive vocal habits remain the cornerstone of management.<br><br>Carcinoma (B) and granuloma (C) usually present with different morphology and clinical settings.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The nerve responsible for motor supply to all intrinsic laryngeal muscles except cricothyroid is the:",o:["Glossopharyngeal nerve","Internal laryngeal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","External laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:2,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve controls nearly all intrinsic laryngeal movements necessary for phonation and airway protection. Damage produces vocal cord paralysis and dysphonia.<br><br>Because of its close anatomical relation to the thyroid gland, the nerve is particularly vulnerable during thyroid and parathyroid surgery.<br><br>The external laryngeal nerve (D) innervates only the cricothyroid muscle.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced laryngeal carcinoma develops severe aspiration after partial laryngectomy. This complication occurs mainly because of impaired:",o:["Vestibular function","Facial sensation","Middle ear ventilation","Nasal airflow","Laryngeal sphincter mechanism"],a:4,e:"The larynx acts as a protective sphincter during swallowing by coordinating epiglottic closure and vocal cord adduction. Partial laryngectomy may disrupt this mechanism.<br><br>Postoperative aspiration is therefore a recognized complication requiring intensive swallowing rehabilitation and nutritional support during recovery.<br><br>Vestibular function (A), nasal airflow (D), and facial sensation (E) are unrelated to postoperative aspiration.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with severe hoarseness is found to have unilateral fixed vocal cord in paramedian position. Which symptom is most likely additionally present?",o:["Aspiration during swallowing","Conductive hearing loss","Vertigo","Facial paralysis","Anosmia"],a:0,e:"Unilateral vocal cord paralysis impairs complete glottic closure during swallowing, predisposing to aspiration. Patients commonly complain of coughing while drinking liquids.<br><br>Voice becomes breathy and weak because excessive air escapes during phonation. Flexible laryngoscopy confirms cord immobility and glottic incompetence.<br><br>Hearing loss (B), vertigo (C), facial paralysis (D), and anosmia (E) are unrelated findings.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 65-year-old smoker presents with hoarseness and neck mass. Biopsy confirms supraglottic squamous cell carcinoma. Which nodal level is most commonly involved initially?",o:["Level I","Level II","Level VI","Retropharyngeal nodes only","Parotid nodes"],a:1,e:"Supraglottic carcinomas commonly metastasize early to upper deep cervical lymph nodes, particularly level II nodes, because of rich lymphatic drainage.<br><br>Neck masses may therefore be the presenting feature even before severe airway symptoms develop. Careful nodal examination is essential during staging.<br><br>Level I nodes (A) are more commonly associated with oral cavity pathology rather than laryngeal tumors.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops aphonia after total laryngectomy. Which rehabilitation method provides speech using pulmonary air redirected into the esophagus?",o:["Pure esophageal speech","Whisper training","Sign language","Nasal resonance therapy","Tracheoesophageal puncture speech"],a:4,e:"Tracheoesophageal puncture creates a controlled communication between trachea and esophagus, allowing pulmonary air to vibrate the pharyngoesophageal segment.<br><br>This method generally produces more fluent and intelligible speech than traditional esophageal speech and has become a widely used rehabilitation technique after laryngectomy.<br><br>Sign language (C) and whisper training (E) do not restore phonatory airflow through the pharyngoesophageal segment.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with blunt neck trauma develops hoarseness and hemoptysis. Which investigation best evaluates laryngeal cartilage fractures?",o:["Plain chest radiograph","Barium meal","Tympanometry","MRI brain","CT scan of neck"],a:4,e:"CT scanning accurately demonstrates laryngeal cartilage fractures, airway narrowing, and associated soft tissue injury following blunt neck trauma.<br><br>Combined with flexible laryngoscopy, CT provides critical information for operative planning and airway management decisions in laryngeal trauma patients.<br><br>Chest radiography (A) and barium studies (E) provide limited information regarding laryngeal framework injuries.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with spasmodic dysphonia is most effectively treated with:",o:["Radical laryngectomy","Botulinum toxin injection","Total thyroidectomy","Antihistamines","Mastoidectomy"],a:1,e:"Spasmodic dysphonia is a focal laryngeal dystonia characterized by involuntary muscle contractions during speech. The voice becomes strained and interrupted.<br><br>Botulinum toxin temporarily weakens affected muscles and significantly improves voice quality in most patients. Repeat injections are commonly required.<br><br>Radical surgery (A) and thyroidectomy (C) are not appropriate management strategies for this functional disorder.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after emergency tracheostomy develops pulsatile bleeding from the stoma several days later. Which complication must be suspected immediately?",o:["Vocal cord granuloma","Tracheo-innominate fistula","Retropharyngeal abscess","Acute epiglottitis","Thyroglossal cyst"],a:1,e:"Tracheo-innominate fistula is a rare but catastrophic complication caused by erosion of the innominate artery by the tracheostomy tube. Sentinel bleeding may precede fatal hemorrhage.<br><br>Immediate airway control, cuff hyperinflation, and urgent surgical intervention are essential because mortality remains extremely high without prompt treatment.<br><br>Granuloma (A) and epiglottitis (D) do not produce massive pulsatile tracheostomy bleeding.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral abductor vocal cord paralysis most commonly presents with:",o:["Severe dysphagia","Complete aphasia","Hypernasal speech","Conductive hearing loss","Inspiratory stridor"],a:4,e:"Bilateral abductor paralysis leaves the vocal cords near the midline, severely compromising the airway during inspiration. Respiratory distress and stridor therefore become prominent clinical features.<br><br>Voice may remain relatively preserved because the cords are still close enough for phonation. Airway stabilization often becomes the immediate management priority.<br><br>Dysphagia (A), hearing loss (D), and aphasia (E) are not characteristic presenting features of bilateral abductor paralysis.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest benign tumor of the larynx in children is:",o:["Chondroma","Lipoma","Hemangioma","Fibroma","Papilloma"],a:4,e:"Juvenile laryngeal papillomatosis is the commonest benign laryngeal tumor in children and is associated with HPV infection. Progressive hoarseness is usually the earliest symptom.<br><br>Repeated endoscopic debulking procedures are frequently required because recurrence is common. Severe disease may produce airway obstruction and stridor.<br><br>Chondromas (A), lipomas (E), and fibromas (D) are much less common within the pediatric larynx.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The safest emergency airway procedure in acute upper airway obstruction caused by laryngeal carcinoma is:",o:["Oral airway insertion","Cricothyrotomy","Tracheostomy","Nasopharyngeal airway","Endoscopic sinus surgery"],a:2,e:"Tracheostomy bypasses the obstructed laryngeal airway and provides a secure route for ventilation below the level of obstruction. It is frequently lifesaving in advanced laryngeal tumors.<br><br>Unlike temporary emergency cricothyrotomy, tracheostomy provides a more stable airway for definitive management and postoperative care.<br><br>Oral airways (A) and nasopharyngeal airways (D) are ineffective when glottic obstruction is severe.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent laryngeal nerve injury after thyroidectomy most commonly develops:",o:["Loss of gag reflex","Facial asymmetry","Hyperacusis","Trismus","Breathy hoarseness"],a:4,e:"Unilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis prevents complete glottic closure during phonation. Excessive air leakage across the cords produces a weak breathy voice.<br><br>Patients may additionally complain of aspiration and ineffective cough depending upon the severity of glottic incompetence.<br><br>Loss of gag reflex (A) suggests glossopharyngeal involvement, while hyperacusis (C) is associated with facial nerve pathology.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The muscle primarily responsible for opening the glottis is the:",o:["Cricothyroid","Thyroarytenoid","Posterior cricoarytenoid","Lateral cricoarytenoid","Interarytenoid"],a:2,e:"Posterior cricoarytenoid muscles abduct the vocal cords and maintain airway patency during inspiration. They are therefore called the \"safety muscles\" of the larynx.<br><br>Bilateral dysfunction causes cords to remain near the midline, producing potentially life-threatening airway obstruction and inspiratory stridor.<br><br>Lateral cricoarytenoid muscles (D) mainly adduct the cords rather than opening the glottis.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A 7-year-old child presents with progressive hoarseness and intermittent stridor. Laryngoscopy demonstrates multiple wart-like lesions involving both vocal cords. Which etiological agent is most strongly associated with this condition?",o:["Epstein-Barr virus","Human papillomavirus","Cytomegalovirus","Streptococcus pyogenes","Mycobacterium tuberculosis"],a:1,e:"Recurrent respiratory papillomatosis is strongly associated with HPV types 6 and 11. Multiple papillomatous lesions interfere with normal vocal cord vibration and airway patency.<br><br>Children commonly require repeated microlaryngoscopic excision procedures because recurrence rates remain high despite treatment. Airway obstruction may occur in aggressive disease.<br><br>Epstein-Barr virus (A) and tuberculosis (E) are not usual causes of laryngeal papillomatosis.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"The sensory nerve supply below the vocal cords is carried mainly by the:",o:["Internal laryngeal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","External laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve"],a:4,e:"The recurrent laryngeal nerve provides sensory innervation below the true vocal cords in addition to supplying most intrinsic laryngeal muscles.<br><br>Injury may impair cough reflexes and airway protection mechanisms, increasing the risk of aspiration and retained secretions.<br><br>The internal laryngeal nerve (A) supplies sensation above the vocal cords rather than below them.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal carcinoma involving the anterior commissure is at increased risk of:",o:["Early thyroid cartilage invasion","Conductive hearing loss","Cerebellar metastasis","Bilateral facial palsy","Otosclerosis"],a:0,e:"The anterior commissure is closely related to Broyles ligament, providing a route for early spread into the thyroid cartilage. This worsens staging and prognosis.<br><br>Tumors involving the anterior commissure therefore require careful radiological and endoscopic assessment before definitive treatment planning.<br><br>Hearing loss (B) and facial palsy (D) are unrelated to anterior commissure involvement.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after prolonged tracheostomy develops progressive narrowing of the airway. The most likely late complication is:",o:["Vocal nodule formation","Bell palsy","Acute sinusitis","Ménière disease","Tracheal stenosis"],a:4,e:"Pressure necrosis from the tube or cuff may cause fibrosis and circumferential narrowing of the tracheal lumen. Symptoms often appear gradually after decannulation.<br><br>Patients commonly present with exertional dyspnea, wheezing, and stridor that may initially mimic asthma clinically.<br><br>Vocal nodules (A) and sinusitis (C) are unrelated complications of prolonged tracheostomy.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest site of laryngeal carcinoma is the:",o:["Subglottis","Aryepiglottic fold","Glottis","Pyriform fossa","Postcricoid region"],a:2,e:"Glottic carcinoma is the commonest form of laryngeal cancer because the true vocal cords are highly exposed to carcinogens such as tobacco smoke.<br><br>Persistent hoarseness occurs early in disease progression, allowing many glottic tumors to be diagnosed before extensive spread develops.<br><br>Subglottic tumors (A) are comparatively rare and often present later with airway compromise.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral vocal cord paralysis is most likely to aspirate liquids because:",o:["Nasal airflow increases","Glottic closure becomes incomplete","Tongue movement ceases","Hearing loss develops","Epiglottis calcifies"],a:1,e:"The vocal cords contribute significantly to airway protection during swallowing. Paralysis prevents effective closure of the glottis, especially during liquid swallowing.<br><br>Patients commonly report coughing after drinking fluids and recurrent lower respiratory tract infections if aspiration becomes persistent.<br><br>Tongue paralysis (C) and epiglottic calcification (E) are not the principal mechanisms here.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with congenital laryngeal web most commonly presents with:",o:["Severe epistaxis","Conductive hearing loss","Facial nerve palsy","Recurrent vertigo","Weak cry and stridor"],a:4,e:"Congenital laryngeal webs partially obstruct the glottic airway and interfere with normal vocal cord vibration. Symptoms usually appear early in infancy.<br><br>Severity depends upon the extent of airway obstruction, ranging from mild dysphonia to significant neonatal respiratory distress.<br><br>Vertigo (D), hearing loss (E), and epistaxis (A) are unrelated presentations.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"Which investigation is most important for assessing vocal cord mobility in persistent hoarseness?",o:["CT brain","MRI spine","Tympanometry","Audiometry","Flexible laryngoscopy"],a:4,e:"Flexible laryngoscopy permits direct visualization of vocal cord movement and mucosal pathology in outpatient settings. It is the essential first-line investigation in chronic hoarseness.<br><br>The procedure helps detect paralysis, tumors, inflammatory lesions, and dynamic abnormalities affecting phonation and airway patency.<br><br>Audiometry (D) and tympanometry (C) assess ear function rather than laryngeal pathology.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient develops severe hoarseness after difficult endotracheal intubation. Laryngoscopy shows arytenoid dislocation. Which symptom is most characteristic?",o:["Sudden persistent dysphonia","Recurrent epistaxis","Conductive deafness","Facial numbness","Hypernasality only"],a:0,e:"Arytenoid dislocation disrupts normal vocal cord movement and glottic closure immediately after traumatic intubation. Patients usually notice sudden severe voice change after extubation.<br><br>Laryngoscopy may demonstrate asymmetry of arytenoid position and impaired cord mobility, sometimes mimicking recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis.<br><br>Epistaxis (B) and deafness (C) are unrelated complications.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The most common symptom of laryngomalacia is:",o:["Expiratory wheeze","Trismus","Conductive hearing loss","Persistent aphasia","Inspiratory stridor"],a:4,e:"Laryngomalacia causes collapse of supraglottic structures during inspiration, producing characteristic inspiratory stridor beginning in early infancy.<br><br>Symptoms often worsen during crying, feeding, or supine positioning and improve when the child is prone or calm. Most cases resolve spontaneously.<br><br>Expiratory wheeze (A) is more typical of lower airway disease rather than supraglottic collapse.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 58-year-old smoker presents with hoarseness and left vocal cord paralysis. No neck lesion is identified clinically. Which additional area must be evaluated carefully?",o:["Middle ear cavity","External auditory canal","Maxillary sinus","Orbit","Mediastinum and lung apex"],a:4,e:"The left recurrent laryngeal nerve loops around the aortic arch before ascending into the neck. Thoracic malignancies may therefore produce left vocal cord paralysis.<br><br>Chest imaging is essential when unexplained left recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy is detected, especially in smokers.<br><br>Middle ear disease (A) and sinus pathology (C) do not typically cause recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important advantage of tracheostomy over prolonged oral intubation is:",o:["Prevention of aspiration completely","Easier long-term airway care and pulmonary toilet","Restoration of normal speech immediately","Elimination of infection risk","Prevention of all airway stenosis"],a:1,e:"Tracheostomy facilitates suctioning, secretion clearance, and patient comfort during prolonged ventilatory support. It also reduces laryngeal injury associated with long-term intubation.<br><br>Patients usually require less sedation and tolerate weaning from ventilation more effectively after tracheostomy placement.<br><br>Speech restoration (C) and elimination of infection risk (D) are not guaranteed benefits.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with muscle tension dysphonia most commonly has:",o:["Structural laryngeal destruction","Tracheal stenosis","Bilateral vocal cord paralysis","Complete aphasia","Excessive muscular activity without organic lesion"],a:4,e:"Muscle tension dysphonia results from hyperfunctional use of laryngeal muscles during speech despite structurally normal vocal cords. Voice becomes strained and fatigued.<br><br>Psychological stress and poor vocal technique frequently contribute to symptom development. Voice therapy is usually highly effective.<br><br>Structural destruction (A) and bilateral paralysis (C) represent organic rather than functional disorders.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy but acceptable voice quality develops respiratory distress because the cords are positioned:",o:["Fully abducted","Vertically fixed","Widely lateralized","Oscillating freely","Near the midline"],a:4,e:"In bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis, the cords commonly rest in the paramedian position. This preserves phonation but critically narrows the airway.<br><br>Patients therefore present predominantly with inspiratory stridor and respiratory distress despite relatively preserved speech quality.<br><br>Fully abducted cords (A) would instead produce marked breathy dysphonia rather than airway obstruction.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal carcinoma undergoes total laryngectomy. Which postoperative complication is particularly associated with salivary leakage through the neck wound?",o:["Chylous fistula","Pharyngocutaneous fistula","Tracheomalacia","Bell palsy","Otosclerosis"],a:1,e:"Breakdown of pharyngeal closure after total laryngectomy may produce leakage of saliva into the neck wound. Fever, wound infection, and delayed healing commonly follow.<br><br>Prior radiotherapy, poor nutrition, and extensive surgery increase the risk of fistula formation significantly.<br><br>Chylous fistula (A) typically involves lymphatic leakage rather than salivary contamination.<br><br><em>(Recall and Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A 61-year-old smoker presents with progressive hoarseness, odynophagia, weight loss, and intermittent aspiration. Flexible laryngoscopy reveals ulceroinfiltrative supraglottic carcinoma involving the epiglottis and pre-epiglottic space. Which anatomical feature most strongly contributes to rapid local tumor spread in this region?",o:["Sparse vascularity of epiglottis","Presence of pre-epiglottic fat space","Absence of lymphatic channels","Rigidity of thyroid cartilage","Lack of mucosal continuity"],a:1,e:"The pre-epiglottic space contains loose fibro-fatty tissue that permits rapid tumor extension from supraglottic lesions. Once invaded, disease spread often becomes extensive and difficult to control locally.<br><br>Involvement of this space significantly influences staging, surgical planning, and prognosis. Imaging evaluation is therefore essential in supraglottic carcinoma assessment.<br><br>Sparse vascularity (A), absent lymphatics (C), rigid cartilage (D), and lack of mucosal continuity (E) do not explain characteristic supraglottic tumor spread.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis develops severe airway compromise but retains relatively preserved phonation because the vocal cords lie in the:",o:["Cadaveric position","Intermediate position","Paramedian position","Fully abducted position","Vertical position"],a:2,e:"In bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis, the cords commonly remain near the paramedian position because of preserved cricothyroid muscle action. Voice quality may therefore remain acceptable.<br><br>Airway compromise becomes severe because the cords cannot abduct during inspiration. This paradoxical combination is a classic high-yield ENT examination concept.<br><br>Cadaveric position (A) is more characteristic of complete vagal paralysis rather than isolated bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve injury.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 4-year-old child develops recurrent episodes of progressive hoarseness and stridor. Bronchoscopy reveals diffuse papillomatous lesions extending into the trachea. Which factor is associated with aggressive disease behavior?",o:["Adult onset disease","HPV type 6 infection","Early childhood onset","Isolated supraglottic involvement","Absence of recurrence"],a:2,e:"Juvenile-onset recurrent respiratory papillomatosis tends to behave more aggressively than adult-onset disease. Early presentation is associated with frequent recurrence and distal airway spread.<br><br>Children may require repeated surgical debulking procedures over many years because HPV persists within respiratory epithelium. Airway obstruction can become life-threatening.<br><br>Adult-onset disease (A) generally follows a milder course compared with aggressive childhood papillomatosis.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with blunt laryngeal trauma develops increasing stridor, hemoptysis, and palpable crepitus over the neck. Which injury most likely explains the crepitus?",o:["Vocal cord edema","Cricothyroid spasm","Superior laryngeal nerve injury","Arytenoid fixation","Air leakage through laryngeal mucosal tear"],a:4,e:"Mucosal disruption permits air to escape into cervical fascial planes, producing surgical emphysema and palpable crepitus. This finding strongly suggests significant airway injury.<br><br>Associated airway edema and cartilage fractures may progress rapidly, so careful airway monitoring and imaging are essential even if initial symptoms seem mild.<br><br>Nerve injury (C) and arytenoid fixation (D) do not produce cervical surgical emphysema.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"The most important factor contributing to the favorable prognosis of early glottic carcinoma is:",o:["Rich bilateral lymphatic drainage","Resistance to tobacco carcinogens","Frequent hematogenous spread","Rapid cartilage invasion","Early presentation with hoarseness"],a:4,e:"Small glottic lesions interfere with normal vocal cord vibration very early, causing persistent dysphonia before significant local spread occurs. Early diagnosis therefore becomes common.<br><br>Sparse lymphatic drainage of the true vocal cords also delays nodal metastasis, contributing further to improved outcomes in early-stage glottic cancer.<br><br>Rich bilateral drainage (A) is characteristic of supraglottic lesions rather than glottic tumors.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 47-year-old professional singer complains of inability to produce high-pitched notes after thyroid surgery. Laryngoscopy shows normal vocal cord mobility. Which nerve is most likely injured?",o:["Internal laryngeal nerve","Recurrent laryngeal nerve","Glossopharyngeal nerve","External laryngeal nerve","Hypoglossal nerve"],a:3,e:"The external branch of the superior laryngeal nerve supplies the cricothyroid muscle, which tenses and elongates the vocal cords during phonation.<br><br>Injury particularly affects singers and professional voice users because production of high-pitched sounds becomes impaired despite preserved cord mobility. Voice fatigue is another common symptom.<br><br>Recurrent laryngeal nerve injury (B) usually produces obvious vocal cord paralysis rather than isolated pitch-control difficulty.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced transglottic carcinoma develops fixation of the hemilarynx. This finding usually indicates involvement of the:",o:["Middle ear cavity","Facial nerve trunk","Nasolacrimal duct","External auditory canal","Cricoarytenoid joint or intrinsic muscles"],a:4,e:"Hemilaryngeal fixation strongly suggests deep infiltration into intrinsic laryngeal musculature or cricoarytenoid articulation. This represents advanced local disease.<br><br>Such findings significantly affect staging and commonly necessitate more aggressive treatment including total laryngectomy or combined chemoradiotherapy.<br><br>Middle ear disease (A) and facial nerve involvement (E) are unrelated to hemilaryngeal fixation.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A child with severe laryngomalacia develops cyanotic spells and failure to thrive despite conservative management. Which procedure is most appropriate?",o:["Radical neck dissection","Total laryngectomy","Supraglottoplasty","Cricothyrotomy","Cochlear implantation"],a:2,e:"Severe laryngomalacia causing feeding difficulty or significant airway compromise may require supraglottoplasty. The procedure removes redundant supraglottic tissue causing inspiratory collapse.<br><br>Most patients experience substantial improvement in stridor and feeding after surgery while preserving normal laryngeal function.<br><br>Radical neck dissection (A) and laryngectomy (B) are inappropriate for congenital supraglottic collapse.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with unilateral vocal cord paralysis undergoes injection laryngoplasty. The main principle of this procedure is to:",o:["Remove arytenoid cartilage","Medialize the paralyzed cord","Paralyze the opposite cord","Shorten the epiglottis","Excise the ventricular bands"],a:1,e:"Injection laryngoplasty improves glottic closure by shifting the paralyzed cord toward the midline. This reduces air leakage during phonation and improves vocal quality.<br><br>Aspiration symptoms may additionally improve because airway protection during swallowing becomes more effective after medialization.<br><br>Arytenoid excision (A) and opposite cord paralysis (C) are not goals of this procedure.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A 68-year-old smoker presents with hoarseness and unilateral otalgia without otologic pathology. Which mechanism best explains the ear pain?",o:["Direct temporal bone invasion","Cochlear ischemia","Eustachian tube obstruction","Facial nerve compression","Referred pain through vagal sensory pathways"],a:4,e:"The larynx and external ear share vagal sensory innervation, producing referred otalgia in laryngeal malignancy. This symptom is particularly associated with supraglottic lesions.<br><br>Persistent unilateral otalgia in smokers with normal ear examination should therefore prompt detailed head and neck evaluation.<br><br>Direct temporal bone invasion (A) is uncommon and unnecessary to explain referred otalgia.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"The commonest site of post-intubation granuloma formation is the:",o:["Anterior commissure","False vocal cords","Epiglottic vallecula","Subglottic region","Vocal process of arytenoid cartilage"],a:4,e:"Pressure from the endotracheal tube commonly traumatizes mucosa over the arytenoid vocal process, producing ulceration and subsequent granuloma formation.<br><br>Patients usually complain of persistent hoarseness, throat discomfort, and vocal fatigue after prolonged intubation. Reflux disease may worsen persistence.<br><br>Subglottic lesions (D) more commonly produce stenosis rather than granuloma formation.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after prolonged tracheostomy develops sudden massive bleeding from the tracheostomy site. Which complication is most feared?",o:["Tracheomalacia","Tracheoesophageal fistula","Tracheo-innominate fistula","Vocal cord granuloma","Retropharyngeal abscess"],a:2,e:"Tracheo-innominate fistula results from erosion of the innominate artery by the tracheostomy tube. It is rare but frequently fatal without immediate intervention.<br><br>Sentinel bleeding may precede catastrophic hemorrhage. Emergency airway control and urgent surgical management are essential to improve survival.<br><br>Granulomas (D) and retropharyngeal abscesses (E) do not produce pulsatile catastrophic bleeding.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with spasmodic dysphonia most commonly demonstrates:",o:["Fluent aphasia","Subglottic stenosis","Bilateral cord fixation","Complete mutism","Involuntary laryngeal muscle contractions during speech"],a:4,e:"Spasmodic dysphonia is a focal laryngeal dystonia producing strained, interrupted, or effortful speech because of involuntary muscular contractions.<br><br>Botulinum toxin injection remains the standard treatment and usually provides significant symptomatic relief for affected patients.<br><br>Cord fixation (C) and aphasia (A) involve entirely different mechanisms of speech dysfunction.<br><br><em>(Dhingra's Diseases of Ear, Nose and Throat)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with bilateral vocal cord paralysis but minimal hoarseness suddenly develops severe respiratory distress. Which statement best explains this paradox?",o:["Vocal cords remain fully abducted","Vocal cords regenerate rapidly","The epiglottis completely seals the airway","Arytenoid cartilages become absent","Cords are close enough for phonation but obstruct inspiration"],a:4,e:"In bilateral recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis, the cords typically remain in a paramedian position. This allows reasonable voice production but critically narrows the airway.<br><br>Patients therefore may appear relatively stable vocally while simultaneously developing life-threatening inspiratory airway compromise requiring urgent intervention.<br><br>Fully abducted cords (A) would instead produce marked breathy dysphonia without major obstruction.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with recurrent respiratory papillomatosis undergoes repeated microlaryngoscopic excisions. Which long-term complication is most associated with repeated surgery?",o:["Tracheal fibrosis and stenosis","Otosclerosis","Bell palsy","Cholesteatoma","Ménière disease"],a:0,e:"Repeated surgical instrumentation may produce scarring and fibrosis of the laryngeal or tracheal airway over time. This risk increases with aggressive recurrent disease.<br><br>Airway stenosis can significantly complicate future management and occasionally necessitates tracheostomy or reconstructive airway procedures.<br><br>The remaining options are unrelated otologic or neurological disorders.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A 56-year-old smoker develops persistent hoarseness and hemoptysis. Laryngoscopy reveals ulcerative lesion confined to one vocal cord with preserved mobility and no nodal disease. Which treatment is most appropriate initially?",o:["Observation only","Radiotherapy or endoscopic laser excision","Radical neck dissection alone","Total laryngectomy immediately","Tracheostomy only"],a:1,e:"Early-stage glottic carcinoma with preserved cord mobility can often be treated successfully with organ-preserving approaches such as radiotherapy or endoscopic laser surgery.<br><br>Voice preservation and high cure rates are major goals in management of early glottic disease. Careful follow-up remains essential to detect recurrence.<br><br>Total laryngectomy (D) is generally reserved for advanced or recurrent disease rather than small T1 lesions.<br><br><em>(Recall and Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"Which anatomical region of the larynx is most prone to early cervical nodal metastasis?",o:["True vocal cords","Subglottis","Supraglottis","Anterior commissure only","Posterior commissure only"],a:2,e:"The supraglottis contains abundant bilateral lymphatic channels that facilitate early cervical nodal spread. Neck masses may therefore be the first presenting feature.<br><br>This differs markedly from glottic carcinoma, where sparse lymphatic drainage delays nodal metastasis and improves prognosis.<br><br>True vocal cords (A) possess comparatively limited lymphatic drainage.<br><br><em>(Snell's Clinical Anatomy)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient after total laryngectomy undergoes tracheoesophageal puncture primarily to restore:",o:["Swallowing reflexes","Speech production","Nasal breathing","Vocal cord movement","Olfactory sensation directly"],a:1,e:"Tracheoesophageal puncture redirects pulmonary air into the pharyngoesophageal segment to generate voice after laryngectomy. This provides more fluent speech than esophageal speech alone.<br><br>Patients require regular prosthesis care because leakage or obstruction may occur over time. Voice rehabilitation remains central to postoperative quality of life.<br><br>Swallowing reflexes (A) and vocal cord movement (D) are not restored because the larynx has been removed.<br><br><em>(Scott-Brown's Otorhinolaryngology)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with laryngeal trauma develops progressive dysphonia after difficult intubation. Flexible laryngoscopy reveals arytenoid dislocation. Which symptom is most characteristic?",o:["Sudden persistent hoarseness after extubation","Bilateral conductive deafness","Complete anosmia","Recurrent epistaxis","Facial numbness"],a:0,e:"Arytenoid dislocation disrupts normal vocal cord mechanics immediately following traumatic intubation. Patients often notice abrupt severe voice change after extubation.<br><br>The condition may mimic recurrent laryngeal nerve paralysis clinically, so careful endoscopic examination is required for accurate diagnosis.<br><br>Deafness (B), anosmia (C), and facial numbness (E) are unrelated findings.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
  {q:"A patient with advanced laryngeal carcinoma develops severe aspiration, airway compromise, and nonfunctional larynx after failed chemoradiotherapy. Which procedure offers definitive management?",o:["Septoplasty","Supraglottoplasty","Total laryngectomy","Tympanoplasty","Injection laryngoplasty"],a:2,e:"Total laryngectomy removes the diseased nonfunctional larynx and permanently separates the airway from the digestive tract. It is often required in salvage settings after failed organ-preserving therapy.<br><br>The procedure improves airway security and aspiration control but results in permanent loss of natural voice, necessitating postoperative speech rehabilitation.<br><br>Septoplasty (A), supraglottoplasty (B), and injection laryngoplasty (E) are inappropriate in advanced nonfunctional laryngeal malignancy.<br><br><em>(Bailey & Love's Short Practice of Surgery)</em>"},
];